arg Church, Khariar\n* Sunni Hanfi Jama Masjid, At-Masjid Pada, Khariar\n* Sunni Jamat Eidgah, NH-353 Near Khariar Autonomous College Khariar\n\n==Markets==\n* Khariar Daily Market \n* Goru Bazar (Weekly Market)\n* New Mraket\n\n==Tourist spots==\nThere are several tourist spots around Khariar. Some of them are listed below:-\n* Patalganga: Patalganga, a tourist spot located approximately 30&nbsp;km from Khariar is a beautiful tourist spot which attracts large numbers of pilgrims from different parts of nuapada district as well as from neighbouring districts. A temple of lord Shiva is also there.\n* [[Tikhali Dam, (Lower Indra Irrigation)|Tikhali dam]]: Tikhali dam, officially known as lower indra irrigation project is a dam located 17&nbsp;km apart from Khariar. It is an important picnic spot for the people of Khariar. Generally it gets crowded in new year occasion.\n* Rusipitha: Rusipitha is located near tukla (Linga Raj)\n*Jogimatha-Tukla\n\n==Culture==\nKhariar's culture is a blend of traditional festivals, food, dance etc. Khariar offers a cosmopolitan and diverse lifestyle with a variety of food, entertainment and standard of living. Khariar has a proud cultural heritage that arose due to intermingling of different religions. The major language used is Odia, which is widely used in each and every part of Khariar region. You can talk here in Hindi Too. English is widely used for official purpose. Nuakhai is the major festival celebrated in this region. The other festivals like rathayatra, dusshera, holi, dipawali, eid, Christmas, chindaguda (Dhanujatra Mahotsav, Anchalika Sanskrutik Utsav, (Chindaguda) are also celebrated in Khariar. Khariar organises Khariar Mahotsav<ref>{{cite web |title=Khariar Mahotsav 2019 |url=https://www.newstrend.news/204881/khariar-mahotsav-2019/ |website=newstrend.news |publisher=Newstrend}}</ref> every year, which attracts a large number of people from different places.\n\nKhariar is basically one of the peaceful town in Odisha . The town remains active from 8AM to 9:30PM usually. The activities of this town includes:- running of schools, shops or very small industries and bus communications. Other than these activities, political activities across the town is also common. In evenings it is a common sight to see youth playing at various fields (mostly at RAJA A.T. HIGH SCHOOL field, Vidya Mandir field, Bhojpur Field, College Field, and Shanti Nagar Field). In fact the veterans also participate in several fitness activities during evenings, like jogging near Canal Road, Padampur Road, Tukla Road, Nehena Road, or College Road.\n\n==Festivals==\n* Ratha Yatra (June\u2013July)\n* Khariar Mohatsav (Jan-Feb)\n* Kartik Purnima (Nov-Dec)\n* Diwali (November)\n* Holi (March)\n* Gurunanak Jayanti\n* Durga Puja\n* Ganesh puja\n* Biswakarma puja\n* Rakshya Bandhan\n* Ram Navami\n* Shivaratri\n* Holi\n* Independence day\n* Republic day\n* Gandhi jayanti\n* Janmastami\n* DhanuJatra\n* Ramzan & Eid\n* Bakareid\n* Moharram\n* Christmas (December)\n* Krushnalila\n* Eid Milad Un Nabi\n* NUAKHAI\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Nuapada district}}\n\n[[Category:Cities and towns in Nuapada district]]\n", "name_user": "Divyam Seth", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eGeography", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Khariar"}
{"title_page": "Center for Arizona Policy", "text_new": "{{advert|date=April 2014}}\n\nThe '''Center for Arizona Policy''' (CAP) is a [[nonprofit organization|nonprofit]] [[conservatism|conservative]] [[lobbying]] group based in [[Arizona]]. The organization advocates for the passage of socially conservative policies in the state. It also produces voter guides to encourage its supporters to elect conservative lawmakers.<ref name=\"dailysun\"/> Over 100 bills supported by CAP have been signed into law in Arizona.<ref name=\"salon\"/>\n\nCAP employees co-wrote Arizona's controversial [[Arizona SB 1062|SB 1062]], which would have shielded business owners and employees from lawsuits if they refused service to anyone based on what they described as sincerely held religious beliefs. In particular, the bill would have exempted such businesses if they refused to hire or service people because of the person's sexual orientation based on religious beliefs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/thetwo-way/2014/02/25/282507942/arizona-gov-brewer-vetoes-controversial-bill|title=Arizona Gov. Brewer Vetoes Controversial Bill|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tucson.com/news/state-and-regional/brewer-vetoes-sb-1062-arizonas-contentious-religious-rights-bill/article_d19766aa-9f42-11e3-b8ad-001a4bcf887a.html|title=Brewer vetoes SB 1062, Arizona's contentious religious rights bill|last=Services|first=Howard Fischer Capitol Media|website=Arizona Daily Star|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/10146/nfl-super-bowl-2015-sb1062-veto-arizona/|title=The NFL, And Sports Leagues, Cheer The Arizona Veto|website=Time|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> The bill was vetoed by governor [[Jan Brewer]].<ref name=\"salon\"/>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Cathi Herrod.jpg|thumb|Cathi Herrod]]\nThe Center for Arizona Policy was founded by [[Len Munsil]] in 1995; he served as Founding President and General Counsel until 2005.<ref name=\"ACU\"/> The current President is Cathi Herrod, who joined the organization as legal counsel in 1997.<ref name=\"herrod\"/>\n\nCAP receives some of its funding from the [[National Christian Charitable Foundation]], an organization largely funded with money from the [[Hobby Lobby]] craft store company. In 2011 the Foundation awarded $236,250 of the $1.6 million CAP received in grant revenue that year.<ref name=\"salon\"/>\n\n==Legislation==\nCAP has supported and lobbied for over 100 bills that have been signed into law in Arizona.<ref name=\"bills\"/> In 2012 alone, 13 CAP-supported bills passed, including a law banning [[abortion]] after 20 weeks of pregnancy.<ref name=\"2012bills\"/>\n\n=== Abortion ===\nThe Center for Arizona Policy opposes legal abortion and has supported legislation to restrict access to abortion.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.azcentral.com/story/news/politics/arizona/2018/07/07/arizona-still-has-law-banning-abortion-its-books-supreme-court-anthony-kennedy-donald-trump/760335002/|title=Arizona still has a law banning abortion on the books|work=azcentral|access-date=2018-11-16|language=en}}</ref> CAP helped to write a bill in Arizona to require that women to explain to their medical providers why they are seeking to have an abortion.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://tucson.com/news/local/arizona-bill-would-require-women-to-explain-why-they-want/article_dc12f339-eeaf-5682-979b-ab714f97abe2.html|title=Arizona bill would require women to explain why they want an abortion|last=Services|first=Howard Fischer Capitol Media|work=Arizona Daily Star|access-date=2018-11-16|language=en}}</ref> Lawsuits against anti-abortion laws have cost Arizona taxpayers more than $2 million, but CAP president, Cathi Herrod, stated that the anti-abortion policies \"outweigh the losses in court.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://tucson.com/ap/state/anti-abortion-laws-have-cost-arizona-millions-in-legal-fees/article_b791a157-55f0-53cb-b240-6fea4f65a579.html|title=Anti-abortion laws have cost Arizona millions in legal fees|last=Press|first=The Associated|work=Arizona Daily Star|access-date=2018-11-16|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Civil Union Ordinances ===\n{{See also|Same-sex marriage in Arizona}}\nIn 2013, the [[Bisbee, Arizona|City of Bisbee]] announced that it intended to legalize same-sex civil unions within the municipality.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-arizona-gaymarriage-idUSBRE93109Y20130402|title=Arizona city poised to pass state's first civil union ordinance|last=Gaynor|first=Tim|work=U.S.|access-date=2018-11-16|language=en-US}}</ref> The Arizona Attorney General, [[Tom Horne]], initially opposed the ordinance, but withdrew a legal challenge after the city adopted an amended version of the ordinance that complied with state laws.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://articles.latimes.com/2013/aug/19/nation/la-na-nn-ff-bisbee-same-sex-civil-unions-20130819|title=Bisbee OKs same-sex civil unions, but only 4 couples say 'I do'|last=Carcamo|first=Cindy|date=2013-08-19|work=Los Angeles Times|access-date=2018-11-16|language=en-US|issn=0458-3035}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://tucson13.nytimes-institute.com/2013/05/28/with-civil-unions-bisbee-sees-growth/|title=With Civil Unions, Bisbee Sees Growth \u2013 Tucson 2013 NYTSJI {{!}} The New York Times Student Journalism Institute - Tucson, Arizona 2013 at the University of Arizona|website=tucson13.nytimes-institute.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-11-16}}</ref> The Center for Arizona Policy opposed the city's move to offer civil unions and responded with a challenge saying, \"If the City of Bisbee enacts a law recognizing a quasi-marital relationship not provided for by Arizona law, it will likely find itself involved in expensive and time-consuming litigation, which it is likely to lose.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.azpolicy.org/2013/04/02/caps-letter-to-the-bisbee-city-council/|title=CAP's Letter to the Bisbee City Council {{!}} Center for Arizona Policy|date=2013-04-02|work=Center for Arizona Policy|access-date=2018-11-16|language=en-US}}</ref> Following Bisbee, the cities and towns of Clarkdale, Cottonwood, Jerome, Sedona, and Tucson also approved of civil unions.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.abc15.com/news/region-northern-az/other/cottonwood-latest-to-approve-civil-unions|title=Cottonwood latest to approve civil unions|last=Press|first=Associated|date=2013-12-19|work=KNXV|access-date=2018-11-16|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181116054226/https://www.abc15.com/news/region-northern-az/other/cottonwood-latest-to-approve-civil-unions|archive-date=2018-11-16|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nCAP describes acceptance of homosexuality in society as \"a deceitful and angry ideology\" and supports what it describes as a \"biblical value that God has a specific intent for sexuality and that it is only realized in the relationship between one man and one woman within the confines of marriage.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.azpolicy.org/2011/06/03/be-encouraged/|title=Be Encouraged {{!}} Center for Arizona Policy|date=2011-06-03|work=Center for Arizona Policy|access-date=2018-11-16|language=en-US}}</ref> \n\n===SB 1062===\nThe Center for Arizona Policy, along with the [[Alliance Defending Freedom]], helped write Arizona Senate Bill 1062, a controversial bill that, if signed into law, would have allowed business owners and employees to refuse to serve anyone based on sincerely held religious beliefs.<ref name=\"salon\"/> Supporters of the bill claimed it was meant to protect the religious freedoms of Arizonans, while opponents pointed out that it was intended to allow discrimination against lesbian, gay, bisexual, and transgender people. Top aides for Arizona Governor Jan Brewer worked closely with CAP in crafting the language of the bill, but Brewer, in response to boycott threats and other economic pressure from various national groups,<ref>http://www.cnn.com/2014/02/26/politics/arizona-brewer-bill/index.html</ref> vetoed it on February 26, 2014, a few days after it passed the state [[Arizona State Senate|Senate]] and [[Arizona House of Representatives|House]].<ref name=\"brewer\"/> CAP and its president Cathi Herrod received a great deal of media attention during the debate over the bill, with several stories highlighting the amount of influence the organization has in Arizona politics.<ref name=\"dailysun\"/><ref name=\"huffpo\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2|refs=\n<ref name=\"salon\">{{cite web | url=http://www.salon.com/2014/03/27/hobby_lobbys_secret_agenda_how_its_secretly_funding_a_vast_right_wing_movement/ | title=Hobby Lobby's secret agenda: How it's quietly funding a vast right-wing movement | work=Salon.com | date=27 March 2014 | accessdate=29 March 2014 | author=Clifton, Eli}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"dailysun\">{{cite web | url=http://azdailysun.com/news/local/state-and-regional/cathi-herrod-at-helm-of-conservative-center-for-arizona-policy/article_fabe26a2-a1ba-11e3-9a43-0019bb2963f4.html | title=Cathi Herrod at helm of conservative Center for Arizona Policy, guiding lawmakers | work=Arizona Daily Sun | date=2 March 2014 | accessdate=29 March 2014 | author=Fischer, Howard}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"herrod\">{{cite web | url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/209841046/Cathi-Herrod | title=Cathi Herrod | publisher=Center for Arizona Policy | accessdate=29 March 2014}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"huffpo\">{{cite web | url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/02/28/arizona-anti-gay-bill_n_4860817.html | title=How One Right-Wing Christian Group Is Leading Arizona's March Toward Conservative Extremism | publisher=TheHuffingtonPost.com, Inc. | work=Huffington Post | date=28 February 2014 | accessdate=29 March 2014 | author=Ashtari, Shadee}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"brewer\">{{cite web | url=https://www.azcentral.com/story/news/politics/2014/03/11/brewer-staff-helped-work-on-sb-1062/6282745/ | title=Brewer staff helped work on SB 1062 | publisher=Gannett | work=azcentral.com | date=11 March 2014 | accessdate=29 March 2014 |author1=Wingett Sanchez, Yvonne  |author2=Pitzl, Mary Jo}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"bills\">{{cite web | url=http://www.azpolicy.org/media-uploads/issues/CAP-%20SupportedBillsThatBecameLaw.pdf | title=CAP-Supported Bills That Became Law | publisher=Center for Arizona Policy | accessdate=29 March 2014}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"2012bills\">{{cite web | url=http://www.azpolicy.org/media-uploads/resource-images/CAP2012LegislativeSummary.pdf | title=Capitol Impact: 2012 Legislative Recap | publisher=Center for Arizona Policy | accessdate=29 March 2014}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"ACU\">{{cite web | url=http://arizonachristian.edu/president/biography/ | title=Biography of the President | publisher=Arizona Christian University | work=ACU Website | accessdate=29 March 2014}}</ref>\n}}\n\n[[Category:Lobbying organizations in the United States]]\n[[Category:Non-profit organizations based in Arizona]]\n[[Category:Organizations based in Phoenix, Arizona]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 1995]]\n[[Category:1995 establishments in Arizona]]\n[[Category:Conservative organizations in the United States]]\n[[Category:Political organizations based in the United States]]\n[[Category:Organizations that oppose same-sex marriage]]\n[[Category:Anti-abortion organizations in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{advert|date=April 2014}}\n\nThe '''Center for Arizona Policy''' (CAP) is a [[nonprofit organization|nonprofit]] [[conservatism|conservative]] [[lobbying]] group based in [[Arizona]]. The organization advocates for the passage of socially conservative policies in the state. It also produces voter guides to encourage its supporters to elect conservative lawmakers.<ref name=\"dailysun\"/> Over 100 bills supported by CAP have been signed into law in Arizona.<ref name=\"salon\"/>\n\nCAP employees co-wrote Arizona's controversial [[Arizona SB 1062|SB 1062]], which would have shielded business owners and employees from lawsuits if they refused service to anyone based on what they described as sincerely held religious beliefs. In particular, the bill would have exempted such businesses in they refused to hire or service people because of the person's sexual orientation based on religious beliefs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/thetwo-way/2014/02/25/282507942/arizona-gov-brewer-vetoes-controversial-bill|title=Arizona Gov. Brewer Vetoes Controversial Bill|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tucson.com/news/state-and-regional/brewer-vetoes-sb-1062-arizonas-contentious-religious-rights-bill/article_d19766aa-9f42-11e3-b8ad-001a4bcf887a.html|title=Brewer vetoes SB 1062, Arizona's contentious religious rights bill|last=Services|first=Howard Fischer Capitol Media|website=Arizona Daily Star|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/10146/nfl-super-bowl-2015-sb1062-veto-arizona/|title=The NFL, And Sports Leagues, Cheer The Arizona Veto|website=Time|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> The bill was vetoed by governor [[Jan Brewer]].<ref name=\"salon\"/>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Cathi Herrod.jpg|thumb|Cathi Herrod]]\nThe Center for Arizona Policy was founded by [[Len Munsil]] in 1995; he served as Founding President and General Counsel until 2005.<ref name=\"ACU\"/> The current President is Cathi Herrod, who joined the organization as legal counsel in 1997.<ref name=\"herrod\"/>\n\nCAP receives some of its funding from the [[National Christian Charitable Foundation]], an organization largely funded with money from the [[Hobby Lobby]] craft store company. In 2011 the Foundation awarded $236,250 of the $1.6 million CAP received in grant revenue that year.<ref name=\"salon\"/>\n\n==Legislation==\nCAP has supported and lobbied for over 100 bills that have been signed into law in Arizona.<ref name=\"bills\"/> In 2012 alone, 13 CAP-supported bills passed, including a law banning [[abortion]] after 20 weeks of pregnancy.<ref name=\"2012bills\"/>\n\n=== Abortion ===\nThe Center for Arizona Policy opposes legal abortion and has supported legislation to restrict access to abortion.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.azcentral.com/story/news/politics/arizona/2018/07/07/arizona-still-has-law-banning-abortion-its-books-supreme-court-anthony-kennedy-donald-trump/760335002/|title=Arizona still has a law banning abortion on the books|work=azcentral|access-date=2018-11-16|language=en}}</ref> CAP helped to write a bill in Arizona to require that women to explain to their medical providers why they are seeking to have an abortion.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://tucson.com/news/local/arizona-bill-would-require-women-to-explain-why-they-want/article_dc12f339-eeaf-5682-979b-ab714f97abe2.html|title=Arizona bill would require women to explain why they want an abortion|last=Services|first=Howard Fischer Capitol Media|work=Arizona Daily Star|access-date=2018-11-16|language=en}}</ref> Lawsuits against anti-abortion laws have cost Arizona taxpayers more than $2 million, but CAP president, Cathi Herrod, stated that the anti-abortion policies \"outweigh the losses in court.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://tucson.com/ap/state/anti-abortion-laws-have-cost-arizona-millions-in-legal-fees/article_b791a157-55f0-53cb-b240-6fea4f65a579.html|title=Anti-abortion laws have cost Arizona millions in legal fees|last=Press|first=The Associated|work=Arizona Daily Star|access-date=2018-11-16|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Civil Union Ordinances ===\n{{See also|Same-sex marriage in Arizona}}\nIn 2013, the [[Bisbee, Arizona|City of Bisbee]] announced that it intended to legalize same-sex civil unions within the municipality.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-arizona-gaymarriage-idUSBRE93109Y20130402|title=Arizona city poised to pass state's first civil union ordinance|last=Gaynor|first=Tim|work=U.S.|access-date=2018-11-16|language=en-US}}</ref> The Arizona Attorney General, [[Tom Horne]], initially opposed the ordinance, but withdrew a legal challenge after the city adopted an amended version of the ordinance that complied with state laws.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://articles.latimes.com/2013/aug/19/nation/la-na-nn-ff-bisbee-same-sex-civil-unions-20130819|title=Bisbee OKs same-sex civil unions, but only 4 couples say 'I do'|last=Carcamo|first=Cindy|date=2013-08-19|work=Los Angeles Times|access-date=2018-11-16|language=en-US|issn=0458-3035}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://tucson13.nytimes-institute.com/2013/05/28/with-civil-unions-bisbee-sees-growth/|title=With Civil Unions, Bisbee Sees Growth \u2013 Tucson 2013 NYTSJI {{!}} The New York Times Student Journalism Institute - Tucson, Arizona 2013 at the University of Arizona|website=tucson13.nytimes-institute.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-11-16}}</ref> The Center for Arizona Policy opposed the city's move to offer civil unions and responded with a challenge saying, \"If the City of Bisbee enacts a law recognizing a quasi-marital relationship not provided for by Arizona law, it will likely find itself involved in expensive and time-consuming litigation, which it is likely to lose.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.azpolicy.org/2013/04/02/caps-letter-to-the-bisbee-city-council/|title=CAP's Letter to the Bisbee City Council {{!}} Center for Arizona Policy|date=2013-04-02|work=Center for Arizona Policy|access-date=2018-11-16|language=en-US}}</ref> Following Bisbee, the cities and towns of Clarkdale, Cottonwood, Jerome, Sedona, and Tucson also approved of civil unions.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.abc15.com/news/region-northern-az/other/cottonwood-latest-to-approve-civil-unions|title=Cottonwood latest to approve civil unions|last=Press|first=Associated|date=2013-12-19|work=KNXV|access-date=2018-11-16|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181116054226/https://www.abc15.com/news/region-northern-az/other/cottonwood-latest-to-approve-civil-unions|archive-date=2018-11-16|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nCAP describes acceptance of homosexuality in society as \"a deceitful and angry ideology\" and supports what it describes as a \"biblical value that God has a specific intent for sexuality and that it is only realized in the relationship between one man and one woman within the confines of marriage.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.azpolicy.org/2011/06/03/be-encouraged/|title=Be Encouraged {{!}} Center for Arizona Policy|date=2011-06-03|work=Center for Arizona Policy|access-date=2018-11-16|language=en-US}}</ref> \n\n===SB 1062===\nThe Center for Arizona Policy, along with the [[Alliance Defending Freedom]], helped write Arizona Senate Bill 1062, a controversial bill that, if signed into law, would have allowed business owners and employees to refuse to serve anyone based on sincerely held religious beliefs.<ref name=\"salon\"/> Supporters of the bill claimed it was meant to protect the religious freedoms of Arizonans, while opponents pointed out that it was intended to allow discrimination against lesbian, gay, bisexual, and transgender people. Top aides for Arizona Governor Jan Brewer worked closely with CAP in crafting the language of the bill, but Brewer, in response to boycott threats and other economic pressure from various national groups,<ref>http://www.cnn.com/2014/02/26/politics/arizona-brewer-bill/index.html</ref> vetoed it on February 26, 2014, a few days after it passed the state [[Arizona State Senate|Senate]] and [[Arizona House of Representatives|House]].<ref name=\"brewer\"/> CAP and its president Cathi Herrod received a great deal of media attention during the debate over the bill, with several stories highlighting the amount of influence the organization has in Arizona politics.<ref name=\"dailysun\"/><ref name=\"huffpo\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2|refs=\n<ref name=\"salon\">{{cite web | url=http://www.salon.com/2014/03/27/hobby_lobbys_secret_agenda_how_its_secretly_funding_a_vast_right_wing_movement/ | title=Hobby Lobby's secret agenda: How it's quietly funding a vast right-wing movement | work=Salon.com | date=27 March 2014 | accessdate=29 March 2014 | author=Clifton, Eli}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"dailysun\">{{cite web | url=http://azdailysun.com/news/local/state-and-regional/cathi-herrod-at-helm-of-conservative-center-for-arizona-policy/article_fabe26a2-a1ba-11e3-9a43-0019bb2963f4.html | title=Cathi Herrod at helm of conservative Center for Arizona Policy, guiding lawmakers | work=Arizona Daily Sun | date=2 March 2014 | accessdate=29 March 2014 | author=Fischer, Howard}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"herrod\">{{cite web | url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/209841046/Cathi-Herrod | title=Cathi Herrod | publisher=Center for Arizona Policy | accessdate=29 March 2014}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"huffpo\">{{cite web | url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/02/28/arizona-anti-gay-bill_n_4860817.html | title=How One Right-Wing Christian Group Is Leading Arizona's March Toward Conservative Extremism | publisher=TheHuffingtonPost.com, Inc. | work=Huffington Post | date=28 February 2014 | accessdate=29 March 2014 | author=Ashtari, Shadee}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"brewer\">{{cite web | url=https://www.azcentral.com/story/news/politics/2014/03/11/brewer-staff-helped-work-on-sb-1062/6282745/ | title=Brewer staff helped work on SB 1062 | publisher=Gannett | work=azcentral.com | date=11 March 2014 | accessdate=29 March 2014 |author1=Wingett Sanchez, Yvonne  |author2=Pitzl, Mary Jo}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"bills\">{{cite web | url=http://www.azpolicy.org/media-uploads/issues/CAP-%20SupportedBillsThatBecameLaw.pdf | title=CAP-Supported Bills That Became Law | publisher=Center for Arizona Policy | accessdate=29 March 2014}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"2012bills\">{{cite web | url=http://www.azpolicy.org/media-uploads/resource-images/CAP2012LegislativeSummary.pdf | title=Capitol Impact: 2012 Legislative Recap | publisher=Center for Arizona Policy | accessdate=29 March 2014}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"ACU\">{{cite web | url=http://arizonachristian.edu/president/biography/ | title=Biography of the President | publisher=Arizona Christian University | work=ACU Website | accessdate=29 March 2014}}</ref>\n}}\n\n[[Category:Lobbying organizations in the United States]]\n[[Category:Non-profit organizations based in Arizona]]\n[[Category:Organizations based in Phoenix, Arizona]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 1995]]\n[[Category:1995 establishments in Arizona]]\n[[Category:Conservative organizations in the United States]]\n[[Category:Political organizations based in the United States]]\n[[Category:Organizations that oppose same-sex marriage]]\n[[Category:Anti-abortion organizations in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "SeminarianJohn", "label": "safe", "comment": "if", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Center_for_Arizona_Policy"}
{"title_page": "Mandarake", "text_new": "{{distinguish|Mandrake}}\n{{Infobox company \n| name = MANDARAKE INC.\n| logo = Mandarake logo.png\n| logo_size = \n| type = [[public company|Public]] ({{tyo|2652}})\n| foundation = 1980\n| location = [[Tokyo]], [[Japan]]\n| key_people = Masuzo Furukawa, President\n| industry = [[retailing|Retail]]\n| products = \n| revenue = {{profit}}\u00a59,865 million [[Japanese yen|JPY]] ([[fiscal year|FY]] 2018)<ref name=\"STAT\"/>\n| net_income = {{profit}}\u00a5658 million [[Japanese yen|JPY]] ([[fiscal year|FY]] 2018)<ref name=\"STAT\"/>\n| num_employees = 168<ref name=\"JCH\"/>\n| homepage = [http://www.mandarake.co.jp www.mandarake.co.jp]\n}}\n{{nihongo|'''Mandarake Inc.'''|\u307e\u3093\u3060\u3089\u3051|lead=yes}} is a [[Japan|Japanese]] retail corporation that operates a chain of [[used good]] stores. Founded as a [[used bookstore]] specializing in [[manga]] in 1980, Mandarake incorporated in 1987 and presently operates 11 retail locations and one [[fulfillment center]]. The company focuses on the purchase and sale of a wide range of [[Collectable|collectables]] and ''[[otaku]]''-related goods, including [[anime]]- and manga-related items, [[DVD]]s, [[CD]]s, [[toy]]s, [[Model figure|figurines]], [[trading card]]s, [[video games]], [[cosplay]] items, [[Cel|animation cels]], and ''[[d\u014djinshi]]'' (self-published works).\n\n==Overview==\n===History===\n[[File:Nakano broadway entrance.JPG|thumb|The entrance to Nakano Broadway in [[Nakano, Tokyo|Nakano]], [[Tokyo]]. The complex houses Mandarake's first store and corporate offices.]]\nMandarake was established by manga artist {{ill|Masuzo Furukawa|ja|\u53e4\u5ddd\u76ca\u4e09}}. A member of the Garo Trio (\u30ac\u30ed\u4e09\u7fbd\u70cf) along with {{ill|Shinichi Abe|ja|\u5b89\u90e8\u614e\u4e00}} and {{ill|Yuji Suzuki|ja|\u9234\u6728\u7fc1\u4e8c}}, Furukawa and the group became known in the 1970s for their work in the alternative manga magazine ''[[Garo (magazine)|Garo]]''.<ref name=\"TRIO\"/> Initially established as a used manga store, Mandarake opened its first location at a seven-square meter storefront in the [[Nakano Broadway]] shopping complex in [[Nakano, Tokyo]] in 1980.<ref name=\"FASHIONCITY\"/><ref name=\"OTAKUCULTURE\"/> Furukawa developed a public profile and promoted Mandarake through his appearances on ''{{ill|We Appraise Anything|ja|\u958b\u904b!\u306a\u3093\u3067\u3082\u9451\u5b9a\u56e3}}'', a variety series on [[TV Tokyo]] in which he appeared as an [[appraiser]] for rare and vintage manga.<ref name=\"OTAKUCULTURE\"/><ref name=\"NYT\"/>\n\nThe store was formally [[Incorporation (business)|incorporated]] in February 1987, with Furukawa's father appointed as president.<ref name=\"JCH\"/> The company subsequently began a process of expansion, acquiring multiple stores in Nakano Broadway and widening its scope to sell a broader range of ''[[otaku]]''-related goods. Mandarake opened its second store in [[Shibuya]] in 1994, and began to steadily expand its number of stores thereafter.<ref name=\"OTAKUCULTURE\"/>\n\nIn 1995, the company established a publishing department that publishes ''Mandarake Manga List'', a [[mail order]] catalog, and ''Mandarake Zenbu'', a premium hobby magazine for collectors.<ref>{{cite web |title=Mandarake ZENBU |url=https://www.mandarake.co.jp/publish/zenbu/indexEn.html |website=Mandarake |accessdate=9 July 2019}}</ref> Mandarake was listed on [[Mothers (Tokyo Stock Exchange)|Mothers]] and became a [[public company]] on July 26, 2000,<ref name=\"JCH\"/> and moved to the Second Section of the [[Tokyo Stock Exchange]] on February 1, 2015.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u307e\u3093\u3060\u3089\u3051\uff0f\u6771\u8a3c\u4e8c\u90e8\u3078\u5e02\u5834\u5909\u66f4 |url=https://www.ryutsuu.biz/backnumber/strategy/h012604.html |website=Ryutsuu |accessdate=19 April 2020 |language=Japanese |date=26 January 2015}}</ref> In 2001, Mandarake launched {{ill|Mandaray|ja|Mandaray}}, an internet [[streaming television]] channel, in partnership with [[Activision]]. The channel, which aired a variety of ''otaku''-related content, suspended service in 2008.<ref name=\"OTAKUCULTURE\"/><ref>{{cite web |title=Mandaray: Mandarake Internet TV |url=http://www.mandarake.co.jp/tv/ |website=Mandaray |accessdate=20 April 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080618085423/http://www.mandarake.co.jp/tv/ |archivedate=18 June 2008 |language=Japanese}}</ref>\n\n===Operations===\n[[File:Mandarake_(4970180671).jpg|thumb|Mandarake New Special, one of 27 Mandarake-branded stores located in Nakano Broadway. This particular store specializes in [[Entertainment robot|toy robots]] such as ''[[Ultraman]]'' and ''[[Transformers]]''.]]\nAs of September 2018, toy sales make up the majority of Mandarake's business, composing 48 percent of all non-consolidated sales. Books compose 14 percent of all sales, ''[[doujinshi]]'' compose 13 percent, and other publications that are not books or ''doujinshi'' compose 1 percent; the remaining 24 of sales are composed of miscellaneous items. Exports compose 17 percent of Mandarake's non-consolidated sales.<ref name=\"JCH\"/>\n\n==Locations==\n[[File:Mandarake Complex, Akihabara.jpg|thumb|Exterior of Mandarake Complex in [[Akihabara]], Tokyo.]]\n[[File:Interiors of Mandarake, Akibahara.jpg|thumb|The fifth floor of Mandarake Complex in [[Akihabara]], Tokyo]]\nIn [[Kant\u014d]], Mandarake operates six locations: four stores located in [[Tokyo]], one store located in [[Utsunomiya]], and a warehouse fulfillment center located in [[Chiba Prefecture|Chiba]].<ref name=\"ShopInfo\"/> In Tokyo, Mandarake's first store in [[Nakano, Tokyo|Nakano]] has operated continuously out of the Nakano Broadway shopping complex since 1980, which also houses the company's corporate offices.<ref name=\"TIMES\"/> Nakano Broadway houses twenty-seven individual shops (also known as annexes or ''kan'') operating under the Mandarake brand.<ref name=TIMES>{{cite web |last1=Miura |first1=Yoshiaki |title=Nakano Broadway marks 50 years, now known as a center for Japanese cultural memorabilia |url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2016/02/02/national/pop-shop-warren-nakano-broadway-marks-50-years-now-known-center-japanese-cultural-memorabilia/ |website=The Japan Times |accessdate=8 July 2019 |date=3 February 2016}}</ref> Each shop is focused on a single category of item, such as [[cosplay]] costumes or ''doujinshi''. Several Mandarake annexes in Nakano Broadway were once independent stores that were acquired by the company.<ref name=\"FASHIONCITY\"/> Additional stores in Tokyo include Mandarake Complex, an eight-story store in [[Akihabara]] opened in April 2008;<ref name=\"JCH\"/> Mandarake [[Shibuya]], which features a [[karaoke]] stage;<ref>{{cite web |title=Shopping in Shibuya |url=https://shibuyaguide.sailingstonetravel.com/shibuya-shopping/ |website=Shibuya Guide |publisher=Sailing Stone Travel |accessdate=19 October 2019}}</ref> and Mandarake [[Ikebukuro]], a store located near [[Otome Road]] that specializes in [[boys' love]] and [[sh\u014djo manga]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Mandarake Ikebukuro Store |url=https://www.mandarake.co.jp/dir/bkr/index-en.html#googtrans|website=Mandarake |accessdate=19 October 2019}}</ref> Outside of Tokyo, Mandarake [[Utsunomiya]] is located in Mageshich\u014d, Utsunomiya,<ref>{{cite web |title=Mandarake Utsunomiya |url=https://www.mandarake.co.jp/dir/utu/index-en.html#googtrans |website=Mandarake |accessdate=19 October 2019}}</ref> while in rural [[Katori, Chiba|Katori]], [[Chiba Prefecture|Chiba]], the company operates Mandarake Sahra, a storage and [[fulfillment center]]. Mandarake Sahra is open to the public for buyback only, and not sales.<ref>{{cite web |title=Mandarake Sahra |url=https://www.mandarake.co.jp/dir/shr/index-en.html |accessdate=8 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Mandarake_Fukuoka.jpg|thumb|right|Mandarake Fukuoka in [[Fukuoka]].]]\nIn [[Hokkaido]], Mandarake [[Sapporo]] moved to its current location at {{ill|Norbesa|ja|\u30ce\u30eb\u30d9\u30b5}} from its former space at {{ill|Sapporo Nanairo|ja|\u672d\u5e4c\u30ca\u30ca\u30a4\u30ed}} on March 17, 2012, tripling the size of the store.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u307e\u3093\u3060\u3089\u3051\u672d\u5e4c\u5e97 3/17\u65b0\u898f\u79fb\u8ee2OPEN!! (in Japanese) |url=https://www.mandarake.co.jp/information/newopen/sapporo/index.html |accessdate=8 July 2019 |date=17 March 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"ShopInfo\"/> In [[T\u014dkai region|T\u014dkai]], Mandarake [[Nagoya]] moved to its current location in [[Naka-ku, Nagoya|Naka-ku]] in 2007 due to insufficient floor space at its previous location; the move saw Mandarake Nagoya expand the size of the store from 266 square meters to 578 square meters.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u307e\u3093\u3060\u3089\u3051\u540d\u53e4\u5c4b\u5e97\u3000\u9326\u304b\u3089\u5927\u9808\u306b\u79fb\u8ee2 \u4eca\u5e7412\u6708\uff088/9\uff09 |url=https://animeanime.jp/article/2007/08/09/2110.html |website=AnimeAnime.jp |accessdate=19 October 2019 |language=Japanese |date=9 August 2007}}</ref><ref name=\"ShopInfo\"/> \n\n[[File:MandrakeStoreSign.jpg|thumb|Signage for Mandarake [[Umeda]] in [[Osaka]], depicting a cartoon image of Masuzo Furukawa.]]\nIn [[Kansai]], Mandarake operates two locations located in [[Osaka]].<ref name=\"ShopInfo\"/> Mandarake's first store in Osaka, Mandarake [[Umeda]], is located in [[Doyama, Osaka, Japan|Doyama]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Mandarake Umeda Store |url=https://www.mandarake.co.jp/dir/umd/index-en.html#googtrans |website=Mandarake |accessdate=19 October 2019}}</ref> Its second location in Osaka, Mandarake Grandchaos, is located in [[Amerikamura]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Mandarake Grand Chaos |url=https://www.mandarake.co.jp/dir/gcs/index-en.html#googtrans |website=Mandarake |accessdate=19 October 2019}}</ref> Two shop locations operate in [[Kyushu]]: Mandarake Fukuoka is located in Tenjin,<ref>{{cite web |title=Mandarake Fukuoka Store |url=https://www.mandarake.co.jp/dir/fko/index-en.html#googtrans |website=Mandarake |accessdate=19 October 2019}}</ref> and andarake Kokura is located in [[Kokurakita-ku, Kitaky\u016bsh\u016b]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Mandarake Koukura Store |url=https://www.mandarake.co.jp/dir/kkr/index-en.html#googtrans |website=Mandarake |accessdate=19 October 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"ShopInfo\"/> Mandarake also operates an online storefront in both Japanese and English. The store ships items both domestically within Japan, and internationally to 83 countries.<ref name=\"SAHRA\"/>\n\nInternationally, Mandarake operated a store in [[California]] from 1999 to 2003; initially located in [[Torrance, California|Torrance]], the store later relocated to [[Santa Monica]] before ultimately closing. The company also operated a store in [[Bologna]] in 2001.<ref>{{cite web |title=Where To Buy |url=http://www.macrossworld.com/macross/where2buy/_where2buy_socal_trip.htm |website=Macross World |accessdate=8 July 2019 |date=9 March 2001}}</ref><ref name=\"FP\">{{cite web |last1=McGray |first1=Douglas |title=Japan\u2019s Gross National Cool |url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2009/11/11/japans-gross-national-cool/ |website=[[Foreign Policy]] |accessdate=19 April 2020 |date=11 November 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Impact==\nMandarake is the largest secondhand [[comics]] retailer in the world,<ref name=\"JCH\"/> with the company's financial success cited by Philomena Keet in ''Tokyo Fashion City'' as \"a testament to the fervor of Japanese fanatics, the dedication of Japanese collectors, and the richness of Japan's material culture.\"<ref name=\"FASHIONCITY\"/> The company sells and purchases roughly ten thousand items per day, and has a [[point of sale]] system that includes over 20 million items.<ref name=\"SAHRA\"/> Its original pricing and appraisal operations are recognized as having a major impact on the secondhand book market.<ref name=\"JCH\"/> The company maintains a policy of purchasing items at roughly half the cost it plans to resell the item, which was noted by ''[[The New York Times]]'' as bringing transparancy to the often opaque appraisal market.<ref name=\"NYT\"/>\n\nThe company actively seeks foreign customers, offering an English-language online store and sales staff fluent in foreign languages.<ref name=\"TIMES\"/> The company also promotes itself as a [[Tourism in Japan|tourist attraction in Japan]], and is marketed as a major destination for foreign ''otaku''.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Heiter |first1=Celeste |title=To Japan with Love |date=2009 |publisher=ThingsAsian Press |isbn=978-1934159057 |page=152}}</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\n===Inventory-related controversies===\nIn 2003, Mandarake was accused of selling improperly-acquired manuscripts by [[Kenshi Hirokane]] and Yayoi Watanabe. The items in question were sold to Mandarake by Hirokane and Watanabe's publisher Sakura Comics, rather than returned to the artists, in an unsuccessful attempt by the publisher to stave off bankruptcy. Mandarake contended that it had no way of knowing that Sakura Publishing was not permitted to sell the manuscripts; the manuscripts were ultimately returned to the artists in a subsequent lawsuit.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Watanabe |first1=Yayoi |title=\u8d70\u308b!\u6f2b\u753b\u5bb6~\u6f2b\u753b\u539f\u7a3f\u6d41\u51fa\u4e8b\u4ef6 |date=2004 |publisher=Creative Publishing |isbn=978-4924718593}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, the [[Tokyo Metropolitan Police Department]] cited Mandarake under the {{ill|Antique Business Law|ja|\u53e4\u7269\u55b6\u696d\u6cd5}} for insufficiently verifying the identities of individuals who purchased items from Mandarake in [[online auctions]]. Under that law, individuals purchasing second-hand goods must identify themselves with photo identification, in order for police to track the movement of second-hand goods that may have been stolen.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Amami |first1=Abe |title=\u300c\u307e\u3093\u3060\u3089\u3051\u300d\u884c\u653f\u51e6\u5206\u3000\u672c\u4eba\u78ba\u8a8d\u304c\u4e0d\u5341\u5206 |url=https://www.asahi.com/articles/ASJ923TCJJ92UTIL016.html |website=Asahi Digital |accessdate=9 July 2019 |date=3 September 2016}}</ref> In response, the [[Tokyo District Court]] suspended Mandarake Complex's online sales license for one month, and fined the company \u00a5300,000.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u307e\u3093\u3060\u3089\u3051\u3092\u55b6\u696d\u505c\u6b62\u51e6\u5206\u3000\u672c\u4eba\u78ba\u8a8d\u4e0d\u5341\u5206 (in Japanese, via Archive) |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160906051828/https://www.sponichi.co.jp/society/news/2016/09/02/kiji/K20160902013280360.html |website=Sponichi |accessdate=9 July 2019 |date=2 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, an original illustration from ''[[Ai to Makoto]]'', one of a series of fifteen believed lost in 1982, was listed for sale in an online auction by Mandarake. ''Ai to Makoto'' publisher [[Kodansha]] requested that the illustration be returned to the company, and issued a statement asking the public to not bid in the auction. The illustration ultimately sold at auction to a private buyer for \u00a54 million.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u300c\u611b\u3068\u8aa0\u300d\u7d1b\u5931\u539f\u753b\uff14\uff10\uff10\u4e07\u5186\u3067\u843d\u672d\u3000\u8b1b\u8ac7\u793e\u306f\u300c\u6b8b\u5ff5\u300d(in Japanese) |url=https://www.asahi.com/articles/ASL5C3RXDL5CUCVL00H.html |website=Asahi Digital |date=11 May 2018 |accessdate=9 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=\u300c\u611b\u3068\u8aa0\u300d\u7d1b\u5931\u539f\u753b\u304c\u7af6\u58f2\u30b5\u30a4\u30c8\u306b\u3000\uff14\uff10\uff10\u4e07\u5186\u3067\u843d\u672d\u3000\u8b1b\u8ac7\u793e\u304c\u6ce8\u610f\u559a\u8d77 |url=https://www.sponichi.co.jp/entertainment/news/2018/05/10/kiji/20180510s00041000262000c.html |website=Sponichi |accessdate=9 July 2019 |date=10 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2012 unpaid overtime lawsuit===\nOn November 16, 2012, a former Mandarake employee petitioned the [[Tokyo District Court]] for the payment of unpaid [[overtime]] from the company, claiming that he was not compensated for time spent at work before and after store opening hours. The plaintiff sought \u00a52,292,246 in unpaid wages and additional damages of \u00a52,194,046. The court ruled in favor of the plaintiff, and ordered Mandarake to pay \u00a52,233,606 in unpaid wages and additional damages of \u00a52,108,165.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u307e\u3093\u3060\u3089\u3051\u3001\u9055\u6cd5\u5c31\u52b4\u8a34\u8a1f\u3067\u6557\u8a34\uff01\u9577\u6642\u9593\u306e\u5f37\u5236\u30bf\u30c0\u50cd\u304d\u306e\u5b9f\u614b\u304c\u9732\u5448 (in Japanese, via Archive) |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130203135805/http://news.livedoor.com/article/detail/7359107/ |website=Business Journal |publisher=Livedoor News |accessdate=8 July 2019 |date=29 January 2013}}</ref>\n\n===2014 shoplifting incident===\nOn August 4, 2014, a vintage ''[[Tetsujin 28-go]]'' [[tin toy]] worth \u00a5250,000 was [[Shoplifting|shoplifted]] from Mandarake Nakano. Mandarake posted an image of the shoplifter taken from security camera footage on their website with the subject's face obscured using [[Pixelization|mosaic censorship]], alongside a statement that the image would be posted with the pixelation removed if the item was not returned within a week.<ref name=\"LEGAL\"/> The Tokyo Metropolitan Police requested that Mandarake not publish the uncensored image;<ref>{{cite web |title=\u4e07\u5f15\u72af\u306e\u9854\u3000\u516c\u958b\u4e2d\u6b62\u3092\u3000\u8b66\u8996\u5e81\u304c\u7533\u3057\u5165\u308c\u3082\u300c\u307e\u3093\u3060\u3089\u3051\u300d\u306f\u516c\u958b\u306e\u610f\u5411 (in Japanese, via Archive) |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140812203344/http://www.sponichi.co.jp/society/news/2014/08/12/kiji/K20140812008732860.html |website=Sponichi Annex |accessdate=9 July 2019 |date=12 August 2014}}</ref> though Manadarake initially stated that it would not comply with the request,<ref>{{cite web |title=\u300c\u6cd5\u7684\u30ea\u30b9\u30af\u306f\u627f\u77e5\u306e\u3046\u3048\u300d \u307e\u3093\u3060\u3089\u3051\u304c\u300c\u4e07\u5f15\u304d\u72af\u300d\u9854\u5199\u771f\u309213\u65e50\u6642\u306b\u516c\u958b\u3078 (in Japanese) |url=https://www.bengo4.com/c_1009/c_1203/n_1905/ |website=Bengo News |accessdate=9 July 2019 |date=12 August 2014}}</ref> the company ultimately elected not to publish the uncensored image.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u8b66\u8996\u5e81\u306e\u8981\u8acb\u306b\u3088\u308a\u9854\u5199\u771f\u306e\u5168\u9762\u516c\u958b\u306f\u4e2d\u6b62\u3055\u305b\u3066\u9802\u304d\u307e\u3059 (in Japanese, via Archive) |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170428093524/http://news.mandarake.co.jp/2014/08/13-1.html |website=Mandarake |accessdate=9 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe incident prompted a public debate over the ethics of Mandarake's actions, and whether they constituted an illegal threat of [[intimidation]].<ref name=\"LEGAL\">{{cite web |last1=Keita |first1=Adachi |title=\u300c\u76d7\u54c1\u3092\u8fd4\u3055\u306a\u304b\u3063\u305f\u3089\u9854\u5199\u771f\u3092\u516c\u958b\u3059\u308b\u300d \u307e\u3093\u3060\u3089\u3051\u306e\u300c\u8b66\u544a\u300d\u306f\u554f\u984c\u306a\u3044\u306e\u304b\uff1f(in Japanese) |url=https://www.bengo4.com/c_1009/c_1203/n_1884/ |website=Bengo News |accessdate=9 July 2019 |date=7 August 2014}}</ref> In an interview with ''[[Weekly Toyo Keizai]]'', Mandarake president Masuzo Furukawa stated that decision to post the image was motivated by a desire to have the item returned, and to deter future shoplifters.<ref name=\"WEEKLY\">{{cite web |last1=Kazuyuki |first1=Ohno |title=\u307e\u3093\u3060\u3089\u3051\u793e\u9577\u72ec\u767d\u300c\u3042\u306e\u9a12\u52d5\u3068\u4f1a\u793e\u306e\u4eca\u5f8c\u300d(in Japanese) |url=https://toyokeizai.net/articles/-/49745 |website=Weekly Toyo Keizai |accessdate=9 July 2019 |date=5 May 2014}}</ref> [[Shoko Nakagawa]] was among the public figures who voiced support for Mandarake's actions.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u3057\u3087\u3053\u305f\u3093\u3001\u300c\u307e\u3093\u3060\u3089\u3051\u300d\u4e07\u5f15\u304d\u72af\u306b\u6012\u308a (in Japanese) |url=https://www.rbbtoday.com/article/2014/08/13/122439.html |website=RBB Today |accessdate=9 July 2019 |date=13 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn August 19, 2014, the shoplifter was identified as Kazutoshi Iwama and arrested by the Tokyo Metropolitan Police after he attempted to sell the toy to another secondhand store. Iwama stated that he was unaware that Mandarake posted his image until after he was arrested.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u307e\u3093\u3060\u3089\u3051:\uff15\uff10\u6b73\u7537\u902e\u6355\u2026\u7a83\u76d7\u5bb9\u7591\u3067\u3000\u73a9\u5177\u300c\u8ee2\u58f2\u76ee\u7684\u300d(in Japanese, via Archive) |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140821194708/http://mainichi.jp/select/news/20140819k0000e040140000c.html |website=The Mainichi Shimbun |accessdate=9 July 2019 |date=19 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Man held over Mandarake theft didn't know about threat until after reselling toy |url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2014/08/19/national/crime-legal/man-held-mandarake-store-toy-shoplifting/ |website=The Japan Times |accessdate=9 July 2019 |date=19 August 2014}}</ref> He was later sentenced in court to one year of imprisonment and three years of probation.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u307e\u3093\u3060\u3089\u3051\u4e07\u5f15\u304d\u3001\u88ab\u544a\u306b\u6709\u7f6a\u5224\u6c7a\u3000\u9244\u4eba\uff12\uff18\u53f7\u73a9\u5177\u76d7\u3080 (in Japanese, via Archive) |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141031052225/http://www.asahi.com/articles/ASGB03DG5GB0UTIL009.html |website=Asahi |accessdate=9 July 2019 |date=31 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Animate]]\n* [[Book Off]]\n* [[Comic Toranoana]]\n* [[K-Books]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em|refs=\n\n<ref name=TRIO>{{cite book |last1=Ono |first1=Koyo |title=The Age of Garo and Com |date=25 September 2014 |publisher=Ao Hayashid\u014d |isbn=978-4792605001 |pages=295}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=JCH>{{cite book |title=Japan Company Handbook (Summer 2019) |date=28 June 2019 |publisher=Toyo Keizai Inc.}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=FASHIONCITY>{{cite book |last1=Keet |first1=Philomena |title=Tokyo Fashion City: A Detailed Guide to Tokyo's Trendiest Fashion Districts |date=2016 |publisher=Tuttle Publishing |isbn=9781462918478 |page=73}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"STAT\">{{cite web |title=Mandarake Inc. Income Statement |url=https://statinvestor.com/40981/mandarake-inc/finances/income-statement/ |website=StatInvestor |accessdate=19 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=ShopInfo>{{cite web |title=Mandarake Shop Info |url=https://earth.mandarake.co.jp/shop/ |website=Mandarake |accessdate=19 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"NYT\">{{cite web |last1=Tanikawa |first1=Miki |title=Appraisal Show Hits Soft Spot in Japan |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/01/26/your-money/IHT-appraisal-show-hits-soft-spot-in-japan.html |website=[[New York Times]] |accessdate=22 April 2020 |date=26 January 2002}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=SAHRA>{{cite web |title=\u307e\u3093\u3060\u3089\u3051SAHRA\u59cb\u52d5\uff01\u301cMandarake SAHRA in Operation\u301c |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=69gToA0a1iA |website=YouTube |publisher=Mandarake |accessdate=8 July 2019 |date=28 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"OTAKUCULTURE\">{{cite web |title=Le magasin de la culture otaku: Mandarake |url=https://www.vivrelejapon.com/ville-tokyo/mandarake |website=Civre Le Japon |language=French |accessdate=19 April 2020 |date=29 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* M. Furukawa, ''Mandarake f\u016bunroku: Maboroshi no manga o motomete'', \u014cta Shuppan, 1995. A history of Mandarake by founder Masuzo Furukawa.\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Mandarake}}\n\n* [http://www.mandarake.co.jp/ Mandarake official website]\n\n[[Category:Manga industry]]\n[[Category:Retail companies based in Tokyo]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on the Tokyo Stock Exchange]]\n[[Category:Retail companies established in 1980]]\n[[Category:1980 establishments in Japan]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|Mandrake}}\n{{Infobox company \n| name = MANDARAKE INC.\n| logo = Mandarake logo.png\n| logo_size = \n| type = [[public company|Public]] ({{tyo|2652}})\n| foundation = 1980\n| location = [[Tokyo]], [[Japan]]\n| key_people = Masuzo Furukawa, President\n| industry = [[retailing|Retail]]\n| products = \n| revenue = {{profit}}\u00a59,865 million [[Japanese yen|JPY]] ([[fiscal year|FY]] 2018)<ref name=\"STAT\"/>\n| net_income = {{profit}}\u00a5658 million [[Japanese yen|JPY]] ([[fiscal year|FY]] 2018)<ref name=\"STAT\"/>\n| num_employees = 168<ref name=\"JCH\"/>\n| homepage = [http://www.mandarake.co.jp www.mandarake.co.jp]\n}}\n{{nihongo|'''Mandarake Inc.'''|\u307e\u3093\u3060\u3089\u3051|lead=yes}} is a [[Japan|Japanese]] retail corporation that operates a chain of [[used good]] stores. Founded as a [[used bookstore]] specializing in [[manga]] in 1980, Mandarake incorporated in 1987 and presently operates 11 retail locations and one [[fulfillment center]]. The company focuses on the purchase and sale of a wide range of [[Collectable|collectables]] and ''[[otaku]]''-related goods, including [[anime]]- and manga-related items, [[DVD]]s, [[CD]]s, [[toy]]s, [[Model figure|figurines]], [[trading card]]s, [[video games]], [[cosplay]] items, [[Cel|animation cels]], and ''[[d\u014djinshi]]'' (self-published works).\n\n==Overview==\n===History===\n[[File:Nakano broadway entrance.JPG|thumb|The entrance to Nakano Broadway in [[Nakano, Tokyo|Nakano]], [[Tokyo]]. The complex houses Mandarake's first store and corporate offices.]]\nMandarake was established by manga artist {{ill|Masuzo Furukawa|ja|\u53e4\u5ddd\u76ca\u4e09}}. A member of the Garo Trio (\u30ac\u30ed\u4e09\u7fbd\u70cf) along with {{ill|Shinichi Abe|ja|\u5b89\u90e8\u614e\u4e00}} and {{ill|Yuji Suzuki|ja|\u9234\u6728\u7fc1\u4e8c}}, Furukawa and the group became known in the 1970s for their work in the alternative manga magazine ''[[Garo (magazine)|Garo]]''.<ref name=\"TRIO\"/> Initially established as a used manga store, Mandarake opened its first location at a seven-square meter storefront in the [[Nakano Broadway]] shopping complex in [[Nakano, Tokyo]] in 1980.<ref name=\"FASHIONCITY\"/><ref name=\"OTAKUCULTURE\"/> Furukawa developed a public profile and promoted Mandarake through his appearances on ''{{ill|We Appraise Anything|ja|\u958b\u904b!\u306a\u3093\u3067\u3082\u9451\u5b9a\u56e3}}'', a variety series on [[TV Tokyo]] in which he appeared as an [[appraiser]] for rare and vintage manga.<ref name=\"OTAKUCULTURE\"/>\n\nThe store was formally [[Incorporation (business)|incorporated]] in February 1987, with Furukawa's father appointed as president.<ref name=\"JCH\"/> The company subsequently began a process of expansion, acquiring multiple stores in Nakano Broadway and widening its scope to sell a broader range of ''[[otaku]]''-related goods. Mandarake opened its second store in [[Shibuya]] in 1994, and began to steadily expand its number of stores thereafter.<ref name=\"OTAKUCULTURE\"/><ref name=\"NYT\"/>\n\nIn 1995, the company established a publishing department that publishes ''Mandarake Manga List'', a [[mail order]] catalog, and ''Mandarake Zenbu'', a premium hobby magazine for collectors.<ref>{{cite web |title=Mandarake ZENBU |url=https://www.mandarake.co.jp/publish/zenbu/indexEn.html |website=Mandarake |accessdate=9 July 2019}}</ref> Mandarake was listed on [[Mothers (Tokyo Stock Exchange)|Mothers]] and became a [[public company]] on July 26, 2000,<ref name=\"JCH\"/> and moved to the Second Section of the [[Tokyo Stock Exchange]] on February 1, 2015.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u307e\u3093\u3060\u3089\u3051\uff0f\u6771\u8a3c\u4e8c\u90e8\u3078\u5e02\u5834\u5909\u66f4 |url=https://www.ryutsuu.biz/backnumber/strategy/h012604.html |website=Ryutsuu |accessdate=19 April 2020 |language=Japanese |date=26 January 2015}}</ref> In 2001, Mandarake launched {{ill|Mandaray|ja|Mandaray}}, an internet [[streaming television]] channel, in partnership with [[Activision]]. The channel, which aired a variety of ''otaku''-related content, suspended service in 2008.<ref name=\"OTAKUCULTURE\"/><ref>{{cite web |title=Mandaray: Mandarake Internet TV |url=http://www.mandarake.co.jp/tv/ |website=Mandaray |accessdate=20 April 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080618085423/http://www.mandarake.co.jp/tv/ |archivedate=18 June 2008 |language=Japanese}}</ref>\n\n===Operations===\n[[File:Mandarake_(4970180671).jpg|thumb|Mandarake New Special, one of 27 Mandarake-branded stores located in Nakano Broadway. This particular store specializes in [[Entertainment robot|toy robots]] such as ''[[Ultraman]]'' and ''[[Transformers]]''.]]\nAs of September 2018, toy sales make up the majority of Mandarake's business, composing 48 percent of all non-consolidated sales. Books compose 14 percent of all sales, ''[[doujinshi]]'' compose 13 percent, and other publications that are not books or ''doujinshi'' compose 1 percent; the remaining 24 of sales are composed of miscellaneous items. Exports compose 17 percent of Mandarake's non-consolidated sales.<ref name=\"JCH\"/>\n\n==Locations==\n[[File:Mandarake Complex, Akihabara.jpg|thumb|Exterior of Mandarake Complex in [[Akihabara]], Tokyo.]]\n[[File:Interiors of Mandarake, Akibahara.jpg|thumb|The fifth floor of Mandarake Complex in [[Akihabara]], Tokyo]]\nIn [[Kant\u014d]], Mandarake operates six locations: four stores located in [[Tokyo]], one store located in [[Utsunomiya]], and a warehouse fulfillment center located in [[Chiba Prefecture|Chiba]].<ref name=\"ShopInfo\"/> In Tokyo, Mandarake's first store in [[Nakano, Tokyo|Nakano]] has operated continuously out of the Nakano Broadway shopping complex since 1980, which also houses the company's corporate offices.<ref name=\"TIMES\"/> Nakano Broadway houses twenty-seven individual shops (also known as annexes or ''kan'') operating under the Mandarake brand.<ref name=TIMES>{{cite web |last1=Miura |first1=Yoshiaki |title=Nakano Broadway marks 50 years, now known as a center for Japanese cultural memorabilia |url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2016/02/02/national/pop-shop-warren-nakano-broadway-marks-50-years-now-known-center-japanese-cultural-memorabilia/ |website=The Japan Times |accessdate=8 July 2019 |date=3 February 2016}}</ref> Each shop is focused on a single category of item, such as [[cosplay]] costumes or ''doujinshi''. Several Mandarake annexes in Nakano Broadway were once independent stores that were acquired by the company.<ref name=\"FASHIONCITY\"/> Additional stores in Tokyo include Mandarake Complex, an eight-story store in [[Akihabara]] opened in April 2008;<ref name=\"JCH\"/> Mandarake [[Shibuya]], which features a [[karaoke]] stage;<ref>{{cite web |title=Shopping in Shibuya |url=https://shibuyaguide.sailingstonetravel.com/shibuya-shopping/ |website=Shibuya Guide |publisher=Sailing Stone Travel |accessdate=19 October 2019}}</ref> and Mandarake [[Ikebukuro]], a store located near [[Otome Road]] that specializes in [[boys' love]] and [[sh\u014djo manga]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Mandarake Ikebukuro Store |url=https://www.mandarake.co.jp/dir/bkr/index-en.html#googtrans|website=Mandarake |accessdate=19 October 2019}}</ref> Outside of Tokyo, Mandarake [[Utsunomiya]] is located in Mageshich\u014d, Utsunomiya,<ref>{{cite web |title=Mandarake Utsunomiya |url=https://www.mandarake.co.jp/dir/utu/index-en.html#googtrans |website=Mandarake |accessdate=19 October 2019}}</ref> while in rural [[Katori, Chiba|Katori]], [[Chiba Prefecture|Chiba]], the company operates Mandarake Sahra, a storage and [[fulfillment center]]. Mandarake Sahra is open to the public for buyback only, and not sales.<ref>{{cite web |title=Mandarake Sahra |url=https://www.mandarake.co.jp/dir/shr/index-en.html |accessdate=8 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Mandarake_Fukuoka.jpg|thumb|right|Mandarake Fukuoka in [[Fukuoka]].]]\nIn [[Hokkaido]], Mandarake [[Sapporo]] moved to its current location at {{ill|Norbesa|ja|\u30ce\u30eb\u30d9\u30b5}} from its former space at {{ill|Sapporo Nanairo|ja|\u672d\u5e4c\u30ca\u30ca\u30a4\u30ed}} on March 17, 2012, tripling the size of the store.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u307e\u3093\u3060\u3089\u3051\u672d\u5e4c\u5e97 3/17\u65b0\u898f\u79fb\u8ee2OPEN!! (in Japanese) |url=https://www.mandarake.co.jp/information/newopen/sapporo/index.html |accessdate=8 July 2019 |date=17 March 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"ShopInfo\"/> In [[T\u014dkai region|T\u014dkai]], Mandarake [[Nagoya]] moved to its current location in [[Naka-ku, Nagoya|Naka-ku]] in 2007 due to insufficient floor space at its previous location; the move saw Mandarake Nagoya expand the size of the store from 266 square meters to 578 square meters.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u307e\u3093\u3060\u3089\u3051\u540d\u53e4\u5c4b\u5e97\u3000\u9326\u304b\u3089\u5927\u9808\u306b\u79fb\u8ee2 \u4eca\u5e7412\u6708\uff088/9\uff09 |url=https://animeanime.jp/article/2007/08/09/2110.html |website=AnimeAnime.jp |accessdate=19 October 2019 |language=Japanese |date=9 August 2007}}</ref><ref name=\"ShopInfo\"/> \n\n[[File:MandrakeStoreSign.jpg|thumb|Signage for Mandarake [[Umeda]] in [[Osaka]], depicting a cartoon image of Masuzo Furukawa.]]\nIn [[Kansai]], Mandarake operates two locations located in [[Osaka]].<ref name=\"ShopInfo\"/> Mandarake's first store in Osaka, Mandarake [[Umeda]], is located in [[Doyama, Osaka, Japan|Doyama]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Mandarake Umeda Store |url=https://www.mandarake.co.jp/dir/umd/index-en.html#googtrans |website=Mandarake |accessdate=19 October 2019}}</ref> Its second location in Osaka, Mandarake Grandchaos, is located in [[Amerikamura]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Mandarake Grand Chaos |url=https://www.mandarake.co.jp/dir/gcs/index-en.html#googtrans |website=Mandarake |accessdate=19 October 2019}}</ref> Two shop locations operate in [[Kyushu]]: Mandarake Fukuoka is located in Tenjin,<ref>{{cite web |title=Mandarake Fukuoka Store |url=https://www.mandarake.co.jp/dir/fko/index-en.html#googtrans |website=Mandarake |accessdate=19 October 2019}}</ref> and andarake Kokura is located in [[Kokurakita-ku, Kitaky\u016bsh\u016b]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Mandarake Koukura Store |url=https://www.mandarake.co.jp/dir/kkr/index-en.html#googtrans |website=Mandarake |accessdate=19 October 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"ShopInfo\"/> Mandarake also operates an online storefront in both Japanese and English. The store ships items both domestically within Japan, and internationally to 83 countries.<ref name=\"SAHRA\"/>\n\nInternationally, Mandarake operated a store in [[California]] from 1999 to 2003; initially located in [[Torrance, California|Torrance]], the store later relocated to [[Santa Monica]] before ultimately closing. The company also operated a store in [[Bologna]] in 2001.<ref>{{cite web |title=Where To Buy |url=http://www.macrossworld.com/macross/where2buy/_where2buy_socal_trip.htm |website=Macross World |accessdate=8 July 2019 |date=9 March 2001}}</ref><ref name=\"FP\">{{cite web |last1=McGray |first1=Douglas |title=Japan\u2019s Gross National Cool |url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2009/11/11/japans-gross-national-cool/ |website=[[Foreign Policy]] |accessdate=19 April 2020 |date=11 November 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Impact==\nMandarake is the largest secondhand [[comics]] retailer in the world,<ref name=\"JCH\"/> with the company's financial success cited by Philomena Keet in ''Tokyo Fashion City'' as \"a testament to the fervor of Japanese fanatics, the dedication of Japanese collectors, and the richness of Japan's material culture.\"<ref name=\"FASHIONCITY\"/> The company sells and purchases roughly ten thousand items per day, and has a [[point of sale]] system that includes over 20 million items.<ref name=\"SAHRA\"/> Its original pricing and appraisal operations are recognized as having a major impact on the secondhand book market.<ref name=\"JCH\"/> The company maintains a policy of purchasing items at roughly half the cost it plans to resell the item, which was noted by ''[[The New York Times]]'' as bringing transparancy to the often opaque appraisal market.<ref name=\"NYT\"/>\n\nThe company actively seeks foreign customers, offering an English-language online store and sales staff fluent in foreign languages.<ref name=\"TIMES\"/> The company also promotes itself as a [[Tourism in Japan|tourist attraction in Japan]], and is marketed as a major destination for foreign ''otaku''.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Heiter |first1=Celeste |title=To Japan with Love |date=2009 |publisher=ThingsAsian Press |isbn=978-1934159057 |page=152}}</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\n===Inventory-related controversies===\nIn 2003, Mandarake was accused of selling improperly-acquired manuscripts by [[Kenshi Hirokane]] and Yayoi Watanabe. The items in question were sold to Mandarake by Hirokane and Watanabe's publisher Sakura Comics, rather than returned to the artists, in an unsuccessful attempt by the publisher to stave off bankruptcy. Mandarake contended that it had no way of knowing that Sakura Publishing was not permitted to sell the manuscripts; the manuscripts were ultimately returned to the artists in a subsequent lawsuit.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Watanabe |first1=Yayoi |title=\u8d70\u308b!\u6f2b\u753b\u5bb6~\u6f2b\u753b\u539f\u7a3f\u6d41\u51fa\u4e8b\u4ef6 |date=2004 |publisher=Creative Publishing |isbn=978-4924718593}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, the [[Tokyo Metropolitan Police Department]] cited Mandarake under the {{ill|Antique Business Law|ja|\u53e4\u7269\u55b6\u696d\u6cd5}} for insufficiently verifying the identities of individuals who purchased items from Mandarake in [[online auctions]]. Under that law, individuals purchasing second-hand goods must identify themselves with photo identification, in order for police to track the movement of second-hand goods that may have been stolen.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Amami |first1=Abe |title=\u300c\u307e\u3093\u3060\u3089\u3051\u300d\u884c\u653f\u51e6\u5206\u3000\u672c\u4eba\u78ba\u8a8d\u304c\u4e0d\u5341\u5206 |url=https://www.asahi.com/articles/ASJ923TCJJ92UTIL016.html |website=Asahi Digital |accessdate=9 July 2019 |date=3 September 2016}}</ref> In response, the [[Tokyo District Court]] suspended Mandarake Complex's online sales license for one month, and fined the company \u00a5300,000.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u307e\u3093\u3060\u3089\u3051\u3092\u55b6\u696d\u505c\u6b62\u51e6\u5206\u3000\u672c\u4eba\u78ba\u8a8d\u4e0d\u5341\u5206 (in Japanese, via Archive) |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160906051828/https://www.sponichi.co.jp/society/news/2016/09/02/kiji/K20160902013280360.html |website=Sponichi |accessdate=9 July 2019 |date=2 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, an original illustration from ''[[Ai to Makoto]]'', one of a series of fifteen believed lost in 1982, was listed for sale in an online auction by Mandarake. ''Ai to Makoto'' publisher [[Kodansha]] requested that the illustration be returned to the company, and issued a statement asking the public to not bid in the auction. The illustration ultimately sold at auction to a private buyer for \u00a54 million.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u300c\u611b\u3068\u8aa0\u300d\u7d1b\u5931\u539f\u753b\uff14\uff10\uff10\u4e07\u5186\u3067\u843d\u672d\u3000\u8b1b\u8ac7\u793e\u306f\u300c\u6b8b\u5ff5\u300d(in Japanese) |url=https://www.asahi.com/articles/ASL5C3RXDL5CUCVL00H.html |website=Asahi Digital |date=11 May 2018 |accessdate=9 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=\u300c\u611b\u3068\u8aa0\u300d\u7d1b\u5931\u539f\u753b\u304c\u7af6\u58f2\u30b5\u30a4\u30c8\u306b\u3000\uff14\uff10\uff10\u4e07\u5186\u3067\u843d\u672d\u3000\u8b1b\u8ac7\u793e\u304c\u6ce8\u610f\u559a\u8d77 |url=https://www.sponichi.co.jp/entertainment/news/2018/05/10/kiji/20180510s00041000262000c.html |website=Sponichi |accessdate=9 July 2019 |date=10 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2012 unpaid overtime lawsuit===\nOn November 16, 2012, a former Mandarake employee petitioned the [[Tokyo District Court]] for the payment of unpaid [[overtime]] from the company, claiming that he was not compensated for time spent at work before and after store opening hours. The plaintiff sought \u00a52,292,246 in unpaid wages and additional damages of \u00a52,194,046. The court ruled in favor of the plaintiff, and ordered Mandarake to pay \u00a52,233,606 in unpaid wages and additional damages of \u00a52,108,165.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u307e\u3093\u3060\u3089\u3051\u3001\u9055\u6cd5\u5c31\u52b4\u8a34\u8a1f\u3067\u6557\u8a34\uff01\u9577\u6642\u9593\u306e\u5f37\u5236\u30bf\u30c0\u50cd\u304d\u306e\u5b9f\u614b\u304c\u9732\u5448 (in Japanese, via Archive) |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130203135805/http://news.livedoor.com/article/detail/7359107/ |website=Business Journal |publisher=Livedoor News |accessdate=8 July 2019 |date=29 January 2013}}</ref>\n\n===2014 shoplifting incident===\nOn August 4, 2014, a vintage ''[[Tetsujin 28-go]]'' [[tin toy]] worth \u00a5250,000 was [[Shoplifting|shoplifted]] from Mandarake Nakano. Mandarake posted an image of the shoplifter taken from security camera footage on their website with the subject's face obscured using [[Pixelization|mosaic censorship]], alongside a statement that the image would be posted with the pixelation removed if the item was not returned within a week.<ref name=\"LEGAL\"/> The Tokyo Metropolitan Police requested that Mandarake not publish the uncensored image;<ref>{{cite web |title=\u4e07\u5f15\u72af\u306e\u9854\u3000\u516c\u958b\u4e2d\u6b62\u3092\u3000\u8b66\u8996\u5e81\u304c\u7533\u3057\u5165\u308c\u3082\u300c\u307e\u3093\u3060\u3089\u3051\u300d\u306f\u516c\u958b\u306e\u610f\u5411 (in Japanese, via Archive) |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140812203344/http://www.sponichi.co.jp/society/news/2014/08/12/kiji/K20140812008732860.html |website=Sponichi Annex |accessdate=9 July 2019 |date=12 August 2014}}</ref> though Manadarake initially stated that it would not comply with the request,<ref>{{cite web |title=\u300c\u6cd5\u7684\u30ea\u30b9\u30af\u306f\u627f\u77e5\u306e\u3046\u3048\u300d \u307e\u3093\u3060\u3089\u3051\u304c\u300c\u4e07\u5f15\u304d\u72af\u300d\u9854\u5199\u771f\u309213\u65e50\u6642\u306b\u516c\u958b\u3078 (in Japanese) |url=https://www.bengo4.com/c_1009/c_1203/n_1905/ |website=Bengo News |accessdate=9 July 2019 |date=12 August 2014}}</ref> the company ultimately elected not to publish the uncensored image.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u8b66\u8996\u5e81\u306e\u8981\u8acb\u306b\u3088\u308a\u9854\u5199\u771f\u306e\u5168\u9762\u516c\u958b\u306f\u4e2d\u6b62\u3055\u305b\u3066\u9802\u304d\u307e\u3059 (in Japanese, via Archive) |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170428093524/http://news.mandarake.co.jp/2014/08/13-1.html |website=Mandarake |accessdate=9 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe incident prompted a public debate over the ethics of Mandarake's actions, and whether they constituted an illegal threat of [[intimidation]].<ref name=\"LEGAL\">{{cite web |last1=Keita |first1=Adachi |title=\u300c\u76d7\u54c1\u3092\u8fd4\u3055\u306a\u304b\u3063\u305f\u3089\u9854\u5199\u771f\u3092\u516c\u958b\u3059\u308b\u300d \u307e\u3093\u3060\u3089\u3051\u306e\u300c\u8b66\u544a\u300d\u306f\u554f\u984c\u306a\u3044\u306e\u304b\uff1f(in Japanese) |url=https://www.bengo4.com/c_1009/c_1203/n_1884/ |website=Bengo News |accessdate=9 July 2019 |date=7 August 2014}}</ref> In an interview with ''[[Weekly Toyo Keizai]]'', Mandarake president Masuzo Furukawa stated that decision to post the image was motivated by a desire to have the item returned, and to deter future shoplifters.<ref name=\"WEEKLY\">{{cite web |last1=Kazuyuki |first1=Ohno |title=\u307e\u3093\u3060\u3089\u3051\u793e\u9577\u72ec\u767d\u300c\u3042\u306e\u9a12\u52d5\u3068\u4f1a\u793e\u306e\u4eca\u5f8c\u300d(in Japanese) |url=https://toyokeizai.net/articles/-/49745 |website=Weekly Toyo Keizai |accessdate=9 July 2019 |date=5 May 2014}}</ref> [[Shoko Nakagawa]] was among the public figures who voiced support for Mandarake's actions.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u3057\u3087\u3053\u305f\u3093\u3001\u300c\u307e\u3093\u3060\u3089\u3051\u300d\u4e07\u5f15\u304d\u72af\u306b\u6012\u308a (in Japanese) |url=https://www.rbbtoday.com/article/2014/08/13/122439.html |website=RBB Today |accessdate=9 July 2019 |date=13 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn August 19, 2014, the shoplifter was identified as Kazutoshi Iwama and arrested by the Tokyo Metropolitan Police after he attempted to sell the toy to another secondhand store. Iwama stated that he was unaware that Mandarake posted his image until after he was arrested.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u307e\u3093\u3060\u3089\u3051:\uff15\uff10\u6b73\u7537\u902e\u6355\u2026\u7a83\u76d7\u5bb9\u7591\u3067\u3000\u73a9\u5177\u300c\u8ee2\u58f2\u76ee\u7684\u300d(in Japanese, via Archive) |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140821194708/http://mainichi.jp/select/news/20140819k0000e040140000c.html |website=The Mainichi Shimbun |accessdate=9 July 2019 |date=19 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Man held over Mandarake theft didn't know about threat until after reselling toy |url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2014/08/19/national/crime-legal/man-held-mandarake-store-toy-shoplifting/ |website=The Japan Times |accessdate=9 July 2019 |date=19 August 2014}}</ref> He was later sentenced in court to one year of imprisonment and three years of probation.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u307e\u3093\u3060\u3089\u3051\u4e07\u5f15\u304d\u3001\u88ab\u544a\u306b\u6709\u7f6a\u5224\u6c7a\u3000\u9244\u4eba\uff12\uff18\u53f7\u73a9\u5177\u76d7\u3080 (in Japanese, via Archive) |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141031052225/http://www.asahi.com/articles/ASGB03DG5GB0UTIL009.html |website=Asahi |accessdate=9 July 2019 |date=31 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Animate]]\n* [[Book Off]]\n* [[Comic Toranoana]]\n* [[K-Books]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em|refs=\n\n<ref name=TRIO>{{cite book |last1=Ono |first1=Koyo |title=The Age of Garo and Com |date=25 September 2014 |publisher=Ao Hayashid\u014d |isbn=978-4792605001 |pages=295}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=JCH>{{cite book |title=Japan Company Handbook (Summer 2019) |date=28 June 2019 |publisher=Toyo Keizai Inc.}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=FASHIONCITY>{{cite book |last1=Keet |first1=Philomena |title=Tokyo Fashion City: A Detailed Guide to Tokyo's Trendiest Fashion Districts |date=2016 |publisher=Tuttle Publishing |isbn=9781462918478 |page=73}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"STAT\">{{cite web |title=Mandarake Inc. Income Statement |url=https://statinvestor.com/40981/mandarake-inc/finances/income-statement/ |website=StatInvestor |accessdate=19 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=ShopInfo>{{cite web |title=Mandarake Shop Info |url=https://earth.mandarake.co.jp/shop/ |website=Mandarake |accessdate=19 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"NYT\">{{cite web |last1=Tanikawa |first1=Miki |title=Appraisal Show Hits Soft Spot in Japan |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/01/26/your-money/IHT-appraisal-show-hits-soft-spot-in-japan.html |website=[[New York Times]] |accessdate=22 April 2020 |date=26 January 2002}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=SAHRA>{{cite web |title=\u307e\u3093\u3060\u3089\u3051SAHRA\u59cb\u52d5\uff01\u301cMandarake SAHRA in Operation\u301c |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=69gToA0a1iA |website=YouTube |publisher=Mandarake |accessdate=8 July 2019 |date=28 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"OTAKUCULTURE\">{{cite web |title=Le magasin de la culture otaku: Mandarake |url=https://www.vivrelejapon.com/ville-tokyo/mandarake |website=Civre Le Japon |language=French |accessdate=19 April 2020 |date=29 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* M. Furukawa, ''Mandarake f\u016bunroku: Maboroshi no manga o motomete'', \u014cta Shuppan, 1995. A history of Mandarake by founder Masuzo Furukawa.\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Mandarake}}\n\n* [http://www.mandarake.co.jp/ Mandarake official website]\n\n[[Category:Manga industry]]\n[[Category:Retail companies based in Tokyo]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on the Tokyo Stock Exchange]]\n[[Category:Retail companies established in 1980]]\n[[Category:1980 establishments in Japan]]\n", "name_user": "Morgan695", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eOverview", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mandarake"}
{"title_page": "Circus Flaminius", "text_new": "{{coord|41.8927578|12.4774218|scale:2000_region:IT_type:landmark|format=dms|display=title}}\n[[File:Circus Flaminius by Giacomo Lauro.jpg|thumb|300px|Engraving of the Circus Flaminius by [[Giacomo Lauro]] in 1641.]]\nThe '''Circus Flaminius''' was a large, circular area in [[ancient Rome]], located in the southern end of the [[Campus Martius]] near the [[Tiber River]].<ref>Pier Luigi Tucci, 'Nuove ricerche sulla topografia dell\u2019area del circo Flaminio\u2019, ''Studi Romani'' 41 (1993) 229-242</ref> It contained a small race-track used for obscure games, and various other buildings and monuments. It was \"built\", or sectioned off, by [[Gaius Flaminius]] in 221 BC.<ref name=\"Humphrey1986\">{{cite book|author=John H. Humphrey|title=Roman Circuses: Arenas for Chariot Racing|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=couetXBQO9AC&pg=PA543|date=1 January 1986|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=978-0-520-04921-5|pages=543\u2013}}</ref> After [[Augustus]] divided the city into [[14 regions of Augustan Rome|14 administrative regions]], the Circus Flaminius gave its name to Region IX, which encompassed the Circus and all of the Campus Martius west of the [[Via Lata (Rome)|Via Lata]].<ref>{{cite book| title=Atlas of Ancient Rome| author=Andrea Carandini| publisher=Princeton University Press| year=2017| p=493-495}}</ref>\n\n==Topography and structures==\n[[File:Maquette de Rome (mus\u00e9e de la civilisation romaine, Rome) (5911809378).jpg|thumb|The plaza of the Circus Flaminius (left of the Theatre of Marcellus in the center), according to [[Italo Gismondi]]'s model]]\nIn its early existence, the Circus was a loop, approximately 500 meters in length stretching across the Flaminian Fields (''Prata Flaminia''). [[Varro]] states that the actual Circus was built around the Fields, which were already a hallowed site for games by the time the Circus was laid in 220 BC.<ref>Varro, ''De Lingua Latina'', 5.153</ref> The ''[[Taurian Games|ludi Taurei]]'' were hosted in the Fields since they were inaugurated by Rome's last king [[Lucius Tarquinius Superbus]] (d. 495 BC).<ref>{{cite book| title=Atlas of Ancient Rome| author=Andrea Carandini| publisher=Princeton University Press| year=2017| p=498-500}}</ref>\n\nDuring the 2nd century BC, this broad space was encroached upon by buildings and monuments.  The circus had no permanent seating, nor were there any permanent structures to mark the perimeter of the race track. By the early 3rd century AD, the only open space that remained was a small piazza in the center, no more than 300 meters long, where the ''[[ludi]]'' (public games) had always been held.\n\nThere were many structures in the vicinity of the circus (\u201cin circo Flaminio\u201d). The [[Temple of Pietas]] lay on the edge of the [[Forum Holitorium]] to the southeast. The Temple of Mars was situated in the northwest. It is estimated that by 220 BC there were six temples, including one to [[Apollo]], in the Flaminian Fields. A theatre dedicated to Apollo was also set up in 179 BC, close to the temple of Apollo, and later rebuilt under the dictatorship of [[Caesar]]. The rebuilding of the theatre necessitated shortening the Circus itself, and required that several temples be destroyed.<ref>{{cite book| title=Atlas of Ancient Rome| author=Andrea Carandini| publisher=Princeton University Press| year=2017| p=507}}</ref> \n\nThe temple of Apollo \"''in circo''\" acquired special significance under Augustus, as a popular legend developed that he had been sired by the god while his mother [[Atia (mother of Augustus)|Atia]] was visiting the temple.<ref>{{cite book| title=Atlas of Ancient Rome| author=Andrea Carandini| publisher=Princeton University Press| year=2017| p=506}}</ref> Augustus undertook myriad new constructions around the Circus, and probably had it paved for the first time. Most notably Augustus demolished the small theater dedicated to Apollo, as well as the temples of Diana and Pietas, to build the [[Theatre of Marcellus]] on the eastern side of the Circus.<ref name=\"Flaminius\">{{cite book| title=Atlas of Ancient Rome| author=Andrea Carandini| publisher=Princeton University Press| year=2017| p=510-511}}</ref> Augustus also built the [[Porticus Octaviae]], which hemmed in the Circus on its northeastern side.<ref>{{cite book| url=http://archive1.village.virginia.edu/spw4s/RomanForum/GoogleEarth/AK_GE/AK_HTML/GF-008.html|title=Rome Alive: A Source Guide to the Ancient City, Vol. 1| author=Peter Aicher| publisher=Bolchazy-Carducci| year=2004}}</ref> Augustus' relation [[Lucius Marcius Philippus (consul 38 BC)|Lucius Marcius Phillipus]] restored the [[Temple of Hercules Musarum]] with a surrounding portico that could be accessed from the Circus.<ref name=\"Flaminius\"/>\n\nIn AD 15, statues to the deified Augustus were erected, dedicated by [[Gaius Norbanus Flaccus (consul 15)|C. Norbanus Flaccus]]. In the early Principate two monumental arches were added at the north and south ends of the Circus, the northern one dedicated to [[Germanicus]] in the year of his death (19 AD), and the southern one to the stepson of Augustus, [[Nero Claudius Drusus|Drusus]].<ref>{{cite book| title=Atlas of Ancient Rome| author=Andrea Carandini| publisher=Princeton University Press| year=2017| p=515}}</ref> \n\n===Location===\nThe ancient arcades which in the middle ages sheltered the workshops of artisans, and thus gave the ''Via delle Botteghe Oscure'' (\"Street of Dark Shops\") its name, were long believed to be the northern substructures of the Circus Flaminius. This placed the Circus north of the ''porticus Phillipi'' between the Piazza Paganica and Piazza Margana.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://exhibits.stanford.edu/nash/feature/c| title=The Urban Legacy of Ancient Rome| publisher=Stanford.edu| access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> In the 1960s the joining of new fragments to the [[Forma Urbis]] identified the arcades as in fact belonging to the [[Theatre of Balbus]] and its connecting portico (the \"Crypta Balbi\" as the archaeological site is known). New excavations combined with the new configuration of the Marble Plan altered the understanding of where the Circus Flaminius was located, moving it southwest closer to the Tiber and placing it on a southeast-northwest axis.<ref>{{cite article| url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/40310726?read-now=1&refreqid=excelsior%3A161880d4ef63c22d17ad222e84d37e0c&seq=8#page_scan_tab_contents| title=The Circus Flaminius| author=T.P. Wiseman| publisher=Papers of the British School at Rome Vol. 42| year=1974| p=3-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite book| title=Atlas of Ancient Rome| author=Andrea Carandini| publisher=Princeton University Press| year=2017| p=500}}</ref> \n\nA previously disregarded reference in the ''[[Mirabilia Urbis Romae]]'' (\"Circus Flammineus Ad Pontem Ludeorum\"), which placed it near the [[Pons Fabricius]], and a fragment of the Marble Plan labelled \"CIR FLAM\" which fitted south of the Portico of Octavia, confirmed the Circus to be roughly located between the Tiber to the south and the Porticos of Octavia and Phillipus to the north, and hemmed in by the Theatre of Marcellus to the east.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://exhibits.stanford.edu/nash/feature/c| title=The Urban Legacy of Ancient Rome| publisher=Stanford.edu| access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://formaurbis.stanford.edu/fragment.php?plateindex=27&record=8| title=Stanford Digital Forma Urbis Romae Project| publisher=formaurbis.stanford.edu| access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\n==Use==\nThe Circus Flaminius was never meant to rival the much larger [[Circus Maximus]], and, unlike the Circus Maximus, it was not just an entertainment venue. It almost certainly lacked a track designed for [[chariot racing]].<ref>[[T.P. Wiseman]], ''Remus: A Roman Myth'' (Cambridge University Press, 1995), p. 211</ref> The only ''ludi'' held there were the [[Taurian Games]], which featured horseback racing around turning posts ''(metae)''.<ref>[[Varro]], ''De lingua latina'' 5.154; also recorded by the ''[[Fasti Ostienses]]''.</ref> The obscure Taurian Games were held to [[propitiation|propitiate]] the gods of the underworld ''([[Di Inferi|di inferi]])'', and seem to have been symbolically grounded in the site itself, as they were never moved to a different circus. Equestrian events were also associated with underworld deities in other rituals and festivals in the Campus Martius. [[Strabo]] makes no mention of equestrian activities taking place in the Circus Flaminius. [[Valerius Maximus]], who is likely to be in error, is the only ancient source that claims the ''Ludi Plebeii'' ([[Plebeian Games]]) were held there. In 2 BC, the circus was flooded for the slaughter of 36 crocodiles to commemorate the building of the [[Forum of Augustus]].<ref> Cassius Dio ''Roman History'' 55.10</ref>\n\nThe Circus also hosted ceremonies related to the [[Roman triumph]], as the Flaminian Fields traditionally figured along the triumphal route towards Capitoline Hill. In 63 BC [[Lucullus|Lucius Licinius Lucullus]] celebrated his triumph in the [[Third Mithridatic War]] and exhibited his spoils in the Circus, including a solid gold statue of [[Mithridates VI of Pontus|Mithridates]].<ref>{{cite book| title=Atlas of Ancient Rome| author=Andrea Carandini| publisher=Princeton University Press| year=2017| p=506}}</ref> Augustus did the same when he exhibited the captured insignia of the enemy armies from his campaigns in [[Dalmatia (Roman province)|Dalmatia]] in the northern part of the Circus.\n\nAccording to [[Plutarch]], the Dictator [[Sulla]] massacred 6,000 prisoners in the Circus Flaminius after the [[Battle of the Colline Gate (82 BC)|Battle of the Colline Gate]] in 82 BC. Prisoners of war from the nearby town of [[Antemnae]] were rounded up in the Circus and slaughtered while the Senate met in the adjacent [[Temple of Bellona, Rome|Temple of Bellona]]; the screams which could be heard from the Temple were a way of intimidating the Senators.<ref>Plutarch, ''Parallel Lives''; XXX.II</ref>\n\nThe Circus Flaminius was also used as a market. [[Roman assemblies|Assemblies]] were often held within it. In 9 BC, it was the venue when [[Augustus]] delivered the ''Laudatio'' of Drusus.\n\n==Later history==\nThe buildings remained in use until the end of the fourth century, when the area was finally abandoned. In the middle ages the ruins of the [[Stadium of Domitian]] (the [[Piazza Navona]]) were often incorrectly identified as the Circus Flaminius. In the 16th century the \"Castrum Aureum\" (\"golden camp\") mentioned in a [[Papal Bull]] of [[Pope Celestin III]] in 1192, was also identified as the Circus.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://exhibits.stanford.edu/nash/feature/c| title=The Urban Legacy of Ancient Rome| publisher=Stanford.edu| access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> \n\nIn 1555 [[Pope Paul IV]] formed the [[Roman Ghetto|Jewish Ghetto]] in the area encompassing much of the former Circus Flaminius. The [[Great Synagogue of Rome]] stands roughly where the southern end of the arena was located.<ref>{{cite book| url=http://archive1.village.virginia.edu/spw4s/RomanForum/GoogleEarth/AK_GE/AK_HTML/GF-008.html|title=Rome Alive: A Source Guide to the Ancient City, Vol. 1| author=Peter Aicher| publisher=Bolchazy-Carducci| year=2004}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n*{{cite book\n  | last = Platner\n  | first = Samuel\n  | authorlink = Samuel Platner\n  | title = A Topographical Dictionary of Ancient Rome\n  | publisher = Oxford University Press\n  | year = 1929 }}\n*{{cite encyclopedia\n  | title = Civilization of the ancient Mediterranean: Greece and Rome\n  | volume = II\n  | publisher = Scribner's\n  | year = 1998 }}\n*{{cite book\n  | last = Humphrey\n  | first = John\n  | authorlink = \n  | title = Roman Circuses: Arenas for Chariot Racing\n  | publisher = Butler & Tanner Ltd.\n  | year = 1986\n  | pages = 540\u2013545\n  | isbn = 0-520-04921-7 }}\n\n[[Category:Buildings and structures completed in the 3rd century BC]]\n[[Category:Ancient Roman circuses in Rome]]\n[[Category:Topography of the ancient city of Rome]]\n", "text_old": "{{coord|41.8927578|12.4774218|scale:2000_region:IT_type:landmark|format=dms|display=title}}\n[[File:Circus Flaminius by Giacomo Lauro.jpg|thumb|300px|Engraving of the Circus Flaminius by [[Giacomo Lauro]] in 1641.]]\nThe '''Circus Flaminius''' was a large, circular area in [[ancient Rome]], located in the southern end of the [[Campus Martius]] near the [[Tiber River]].<ref>Pier Luigi Tucci, 'Nuove ricerche sulla topografia dell\u2019area del circo Flaminio\u2019, ''Studi Romani'' 41 (1993) 229-242</ref> It contained a small race-track used for obscure games, and various other buildings and monuments. It was \"built\", or sectioned off, by [[Gaius Flaminius]] in 221 BC.<ref name=\"Humphrey1986\">{{cite book|author=John H. Humphrey|title=Roman Circuses: Arenas for Chariot Racing|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=couetXBQO9AC&pg=PA543|date=1 January 1986|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=978-0-520-04921-5|pages=543\u2013}}</ref> After [[Augustus]] divided the city into [[14 regions of Augustan Rome|14 administrative regions]], the Circus Flaminius gave its name to Region IX, which encompassed the Circus and all of the Campus Martius west of the [[Via Lata (Rome)|Via Lata]].<ref>{{cite book| title=Atlas of Ancient Rome| author=Andrea Carandini| publisher=Princeton University Press| year=2017| p=493-495}}</ref>\n\n==Topography and structures==\n[[File:Maquette de Rome (mus\u00e9e de la civilisation romaine, Rome) (5911809378).jpg|thumb|The plaza of the Circus Flaminius (left of the Theatre of Marcellus in the center), according to [[Italo Gismondi]]'s model]]\nIn its early existence, the Circus was a loop, approximately 500 meters in length stretching across the Flaminian Fields (''Prata Flaminia''). [[Varro]] states that the actual Circus was built around the Fields, which were already a hallowed site for games by the time the Circus was laid in 220 BC.<ref>Varro, ''De Lingua Latina'', V.153</ref> The ''[[Taurian Games|ludi Taurei]]'' were hosted in the Fields since they were inaugurated by Rome's last king [[Lucius Tarquinius Superbus]] (d. 495 BC).<ref>{{cite book| title=Atlas of Ancient Rome| author=Andrea Carandini| publisher=Princeton University Press| year=2017| p=498-500}}</ref>\n\nDuring the 2nd century BC, this broad space was encroached upon by buildings and monuments.  The circus had no permanent seating, nor were there any permanent structures to mark the perimeter of the race track. By the early 3rd century AD, the only open space that remained was a small piazza in the center, no more than 300 meters long, where the ''[[ludi]]'' (public games) had always been held.\n\nThere were many structures in the vicinity of the circus (\u201cin circo Flaminio\u201d). The [[Temple of Pietas]] lay on the edge of the [[Forum Holitorium]] to the southeast. The Temple of Mars was situated in the northwest. It is estimated that by 220 BC there were six temples, including one to [[Apollo]], in the Flaminian Fields. A theatre dedicated to Apollo was also set up in 179 BC, close to the temple of Apollo, and later rebuilt under the dictatorship of [[Caesar]]. The rebuilding of the theatre necessitated shortening the Circus itself, and required that several temples be destroyed.<ref>{{cite book| title=Atlas of Ancient Rome| author=Andrea Carandini| publisher=Princeton University Press| year=2017| p=507}}</ref> \n\nThe temple of Apollo \"''in circo''\" acquired special significance under Augustus, as a popular legend developed that he had been sired by the god while his mother [[Atia (mother of Augustus)|Atia]] was visiting the temple.<ref>{{cite book| title=Atlas of Ancient Rome| author=Andrea Carandini| publisher=Princeton University Press| year=2017| p=506}}</ref> Augustus undertook myriad new constructions around the Circus, and probably had it paved for the first time. Most notably Augustus demolished the small theater dedicated to Apollo, as well as the temples of Diana and Pietas, to build the [[Theatre of Marcellus]] on the eastern side of the Circus.<ref name=\"Flaminius\">{{cite book| title=Atlas of Ancient Rome| author=Andrea Carandini| publisher=Princeton University Press| year=2017| p=510-511}}</ref> Augustus also built the [[Porticus Octaviae]], which hemmed in the Circus on its northeastern side.<ref>{{cite book| url=http://archive1.village.virginia.edu/spw4s/RomanForum/GoogleEarth/AK_GE/AK_HTML/GF-008.html|title=Rome Alive: A Source Guide to the Ancient City, Vol. 1| author=Peter Aicher| publisher=Bolchazy-Carducci| year=2004}}</ref> Augustus' relation [[Lucius Marcius Philippus (consul 38 BC)|Lucius Marcius Phillipus]] restored the [[Temple of Hercules Musarum]] with a surrounding portico that could be accessed from the Circus.<ref name=\"Flaminius\"/>\n\nIn AD 15, statues to the deified Augustus were erected, dedicated by [[Gaius Norbanus Flaccus (consul 15)|C. Norbanus Flaccus]]. In the early Principate two monumental arches were added at the north and south ends of the Circus, the northern one dedicated to [[Germanicus]] in the year of his death (19 AD), and the southern one to the stepson of Augustus, [[Nero Claudius Drusus|Drusus]].<ref>{{cite book| title=Atlas of Ancient Rome| author=Andrea Carandini| publisher=Princeton University Press| year=2017| p=515}}</ref> \n\n===Location===\nThe ancient arcades which in the middle ages sheltered the workshops of artisans, and thus gave the ''Via delle Botteghe Oscure'' (\"Street of Dark Shops\") its name, were long believed to be the northern substructures of the Circus Flaminius. This placed the Circus north of the ''porticus Phillipi'' between the Piazza Paganica and Piazza Margana.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://exhibits.stanford.edu/nash/feature/c| title=The Urban Legacy of Ancient Rome| publisher=Stanford.edu| access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> In the 1960s the joining of new fragments to the [[Forma Urbis]] identified the arcades as in fact belonging to the [[Theatre of Balbus]] and its connecting portico (the \"Crypta Balbi\" as the archaeological site is known). New excavations combined with the new configuration of the Marble Plan altered the understanding of where the Circus Flaminius was located, moving it southwest closer to the Tiber and placing it on a southeast-northwest axis.<ref>{{cite article| url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/40310726?read-now=1&refreqid=excelsior%3A161880d4ef63c22d17ad222e84d37e0c&seq=8#page_scan_tab_contents| title=The Circus Flaminius| author=T.P. Wiseman| publisher=Papers of the British School at Rome Vol. 42| year=1974| p=3-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite book| title=Atlas of Ancient Rome| author=Andrea Carandini| publisher=Princeton University Press| year=2017| p=500}}</ref> \n\nA previously disregarded reference in the ''[[Mirabilia Urbis Romae]]'' (\"Circus Flammineus Ad Pontem Ludeorum\"), which placed it near the [[Pons Fabricius]], and a fragment of the Marble Plan labelled \"CIR FLAM\" which fitted south of the Portico of Octavia, confirmed the Circus to be roughly located between the Tiber to the south and the Porticos of Octavia and Phillipus to the north, and hemmed in by the Theatre of Marcellus to the east.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://exhibits.stanford.edu/nash/feature/c| title=The Urban Legacy of Ancient Rome| publisher=Stanford.edu| access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://formaurbis.stanford.edu/fragment.php?plateindex=27&record=8| title=Stanford Digital Forma Urbis Romae Project| publisher=formaurbis.stanford.edu| access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\n==Use==\nThe Circus Flaminius was never meant to rival the much larger [[Circus Maximus]], and, unlike the Circus Maximus, it was not just an entertainment venue. It almost certainly lacked a track designed for [[chariot racing]].<ref>[[T.P. Wiseman]], ''Remus: A Roman Myth'' (Cambridge University Press, 1995), p. 211</ref> The only ''ludi'' held there were the [[Taurian Games]], which featured horseback racing around turning posts ''(metae)''.<ref>[[Varro]], ''De lingua latina'' 5.154; also recorded by the ''[[Fasti Ostienses]]''.</ref> The obscure Taurian Games were held to [[propitiation|propitiate]] the gods of the underworld ''([[Di Inferi|di inferi]])'', and seem to have been symbolically grounded in the site itself, as they were never moved to a different circus. Equestrian events were also associated with underworld deities in other rituals and festivals in the Campus Martius. [[Strabo]] makes no mention of equestrian activities taking place in the Circus Flaminius. [[Valerius Maximus]], who is likely to be in error, is the only ancient source that claims the ''Ludi Plebeii'' ([[Plebeian Games]]) were held there. In 2 BC, the circus was flooded for the slaughter of 36 crocodiles to commemorate the building of the [[Forum of Augustus]].<ref> Cassius Dio ''Roman History'' 55.10</ref>\n\nThe Circus also hosted ceremonies related to the [[Roman triumph]], as the Flaminian Fields traditionally figured along the triumphal route towards Capitoline Hill. In 63 BC [[Lucullus|Lucius Licinius Lucullus]] celebrated his triumph in the [[Third Mithridatic War]] and exhibited his spoils in the Circus, including a solid gold statue of [[Mithridates VI of Pontus|Mithridates]].<ref>{{cite book| title=Atlas of Ancient Rome| author=Andrea Carandini| publisher=Princeton University Press| year=2017| p=506}}</ref> Augustus did the same when he exhibited the captured insignia of the enemy armies from his campaigns in [[Dalmatia (Roman province)|Dalmatia]] in the northern part of the Circus.\n\nAccording to [[Plutarch]], the Dictator [[Sulla]] massacred 6,000 prisoners in the Circus Flaminius after the [[Battle of the Colline Gate (82 BC)|Battle of the Colline Gate]] in 82 BC. Prisoners of war from the nearby town of [[Antemnae]] were rounded up in the Circus and slaughtered while the Senate met in the adjacent [[Temple of Bellona, Rome|Temple of Bellona]]; the screams which could be heard from the Temple were a way of intimidating the Senators.<ref>Plutarch, ''Parallel Lives''; XXX.II</ref>\n\nThe Circus Flaminius was also used as a market. [[Roman assemblies|Assemblies]] were often held within it. In 9 BC, it was the venue when [[Augustus]] delivered the ''Laudatio'' of Drusus.\n\n==Later history==\nThe buildings remained in use until the end of the fourth century, when the area was finally abandoned. In the middle ages the ruins of the [[Stadium of Domitian]] (the [[Piazza Navona]]) were often incorrectly identified as the Circus Flaminius. In the 16th century the \"Castrum Aureum\" (\"golden camp\") mentioned in a [[Papal Bull]] of [[Pope Celestin III]] in 1192, was also identified as the Circus.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://exhibits.stanford.edu/nash/feature/c| title=The Urban Legacy of Ancient Rome| publisher=Stanford.edu| access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> \n\nIn 1555 [[Pope Paul IV]] formed the [[Roman Ghetto|Jewish Ghetto]] in the area encompassing much of the former Circus Flaminius. The [[Great Synagogue of Rome]] stands roughly where the southern end of the arena was located.<ref>{{cite book| url=http://archive1.village.virginia.edu/spw4s/RomanForum/GoogleEarth/AK_GE/AK_HTML/GF-008.html|title=Rome Alive: A Source Guide to the Ancient City, Vol. 1| author=Peter Aicher| publisher=Bolchazy-Carducci| year=2004}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n*{{cite book\n  | last = Platner\n  | first = Samuel\n  | authorlink = Samuel Platner\n  | title = A Topographical Dictionary of Ancient Rome\n  | publisher = Oxford University Press\n  | year = 1929 }}\n*{{cite encyclopedia\n  | title = Civilization of the ancient Mediterranean: Greece and Rome\n  | volume = II\n  | publisher = Scribner's\n  | year = 1998 }}\n*{{cite book\n  | last = Humphrey\n  | first = John\n  | authorlink = \n  | title = Roman Circuses: Arenas for Chariot Racing\n  | publisher = Butler & Tanner Ltd.\n  | year = 1986\n  | pages = 540\u2013545\n  | isbn = 0-520-04921-7 }}\n\n[[Category:Buildings and structures completed in the 3rd century BC]]\n[[Category:Ancient Roman circuses in Rome]]\n[[Category:Topography of the ancient city of Rome]]\n", "name_user": "Volubilis90", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTopography and structures", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Circus_Flaminius"}
{"title_page": "Brooklyn Museum Libraries and Archives", "text_new": "{{Infobox museum\n|name = Brooklyn Museum Libraries and Archives\n|library_logo =\n|image=File:G1015 Sa5 Sanson Atlas table of contents detail.jpeg\n|caption=Nicolas Sanson. Atlas nouveau, 1692. Table of contents, detail.\n|map_type=New York City\n|map_caption = Location within New York City\n|coordinates = {{coord|40.6712062|-73.9636306|display=inline}}\n|established= {{Start date|1823}}\n|location= 200 Eastern Parkway, [[Brooklyn]], New York, NY\n|type= [[Library]]\n|collection_size= 300,000 volumes and 3,000+ linear feet archives\n|annual_circulation=\n|pop_served= \n|budget=\n|director= Deirdre Lawrence (Principal Librarian)\n|num_employees=\n|website={{url|http://www.brooklynmuseum.org/opencollection/archives/}}\n}}\nThe '''Brooklyn Museum Libraries and Archives''' holds approximately 300,000 volumes<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Lawrence|first1=Deirdre E. |title=Beyond the Galleries: The Brooklyn Museum Library Shares Its Treasures|journal=Fine Art Connoisseur|date=2008|url=http://nyarc.org/arcade/brooklyn/articles/FA_BehindScenes.pdf}}</ref> and over 3,000 linear feet of archives related to the history of the museum and its collections. The library collections comprise books, periodicals, auction catalogs, artist and institutional files as well as special collections containing photographs, sketches, artists' books, rare books and trade catalogues. The museum archives contains institutional records, curatorial correspondence, expedition reports, and other related textual and visual records dating to the founding of the institution.\n{{TOC limit|2}}\n\n==History==\nThe [[Brooklyn Museum]] evolved from the Brooklyn Apprentices' Library Association, founded in 1823, and the first free and circulating library in Brooklyn. In 1831, the library acquired its first painting, joining a developing book collection. According to the Minutes of the Apprentices' Library from January 31, 1835: \"[[Walter Whitman]] acting librarian presented a Report this evening, in which it is stated that there are now about 1200 volumes in the library in a proper \nstate for being drawn out; and that the number of Readers is 172.\"<ref>{{cite journal|title=Minutes of the Brooklyn Apprentices' Library Association, 1:84.|journal=Brooklyn Museum Archives}}</ref>\n\nBy the 1840s, the public demand for educational programs resulted in the reorganization of the library with the adoption by the association of a revised charter under the name of the Brooklyn Institute and the library was housed in a new building.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Lawrence|first1=Deirdre|title=The Evolution of a Library: The Brooklyn Museum of Art Libraries and Archives|journal=Art Documentation|date=1999|volume=18|issue=1|pages=10\u201313}}</ref> Evening classes were offered, the first exhibition of paintings was held and library acquisition funds became available. The library accession records document early institutional interest in the world at large. An early acquisition is currently in the museum's long term installation, ''Connecting Cultures''.\n\nOver the next forty years, the Brooklyn Institute grew and was reorganized into the Brooklyn Institute of Arts & Sciences, which eventually became the parent organization of the [[Brooklyn Museum]], [[Brooklyn Children's Museum]], the [[Brooklyn Academy of Music]] (BAM) and the [[Brooklyn Botanic Garden]]. During the late 1880s, plans were established to revitalize the institute in order \u2033to make the property of the Institute the nucleus of a broad and comprehensive institution for the advancement of science and art...\u2033<ref>{{cite book|title=Brooklyn Institute of Arts and Sciences. Third Yearbook of the Brooklyn Institute|date=1891|publisher=Brooklyn: Press of Eagle Book}}</ref> After an architectural competition held in 1893, the firm of [[McKim, Mead & White]] was chosen to design a building to house the Brooklyn Museum and its library.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Lawrence|first1=Deirdre|title=The Evolution of a Library: The Brooklyn Museum of Art Libraries and Archives|journal=Art Documentation|date=1999|volume=18|issue=1|pages=10\u201313}}</ref>\n\nThe early 1900s saw reorganization of the original Apprentices' Library by the museum librarians who kept portions of the collection that supported research on the museum's object collections and transferred the rest to other libraries in Brooklyn and other institutions.\n\n[[William Henry Goodyear]], the museum's first Curator of Fine Arts (1890-1923), founding museum librarian Susan A. Hutchinson (1900\u201335) and [[Stewart Culin]], the museum's first Curator of Ethnology (1903\u201329), laid the foundation of the research and object collections. Some of the rarest material in the library collection today, such as a set of documentary photographs of Mexico and Central America taken by [[Alfred P. Maudslay]] in the 1880s, was acquired under their direction. After Stewart Culin died, the trustees acquired his archives and personal library of nearly 7,000 titles, focused primarily on the arts and culture of the Americas, Asia, Africa, and Eastern Europe.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Lawrence|first1=Deirdre|title=The Evolution of a Library: The Brooklyn Museum of Art Libraries and Archives|journal=Art Documentation|date=1999|volume=18|issue=1|pages=10\u201313}}</ref>\n\n==The Libraries==\n\nToday the Brooklyn Museum has two research libraries\u2014the Art Reference Library and the Wilbour Library of Egyptology\u2014in addition to the museum archives which support research on the museum, its history and collections as well as the broader areas of art and cultural history.\n\n===Wilbour Library of Egyptology===\nThe Wilbour Library is named after [[Charles Edwin Wilbour]], 1833\u201396, one of America's first Egyptologists. During his travels to Egypt, Wilbour visited temples and tombs and copied inscriptions found on monuments in the field. He built an important resource on Ancient Egypt by collecting books from fellow Egyptologists abroad, as well as from dealers and scholarly publishers, developing his personal library as a resource to educate himself. Wilbour's personal library was enriched with scholarly annotations containing corrections and additions to the published text which are of value today as they offer unique information. In 1916, Wilbour's children offered his antiquities and library collection to the Brooklyn Museum as a memorial to their father.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Compiled by|last2=Cook, Jr.|first2=William Burt|title=Catalogue of the Egyptological and Other Books From the Collection of the Late Edwin Wilbour|date=1924|publisher=Brooklyn Museum|location=Brooklyn, New York}}</ref> After this initial donation, Wilbour's heirs continued to donate objects to the museum. In 1932, the Charles Edwin Wilbour Fund was set up by Victor Wilbour to support both the library and the Egyptian collection at the museum.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Rose|first1=Mark|title=Wilbour's Legacy|journal=Archaeology|date=August 18, 2005|url=http://archive.archaeology.org/online/reviews/wilbour/index.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Fazzini|first1=Richard A.|last2=Romano|first2=James F.|last3=Cody|first3=Madeleine E.|title=Art for eternity : masterworks from ancient Egypt|date=1999|publisher=Brooklyn Museum of Art, in association with Scala Publishers|location=Brooklyn, NY}}</ref>\n\n===Museum Archives===\nIn 1985, the Brooklyn Museum established the archives as part of the library. Textual and visual materials are available to support users in understanding the museum's object collections as well as its history and programs. Exchanges between curators and artists, collectors and donors, as well as exhibition files containing information on specific artists or works of art that have been exhibited at the museum, and object documentation tracing how an object was acquired, and more can all be found in the archives.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Lawrence|first1=Deirdre|title=The Evolution of a Library: The Brooklyn Museum of Art Libraries and Archives|journal=Art Documentation|date=1999|volume=18|issue=1|pages=10\u201313}}</ref>\n\n===Collection highlights===\nToday the Brooklyn Museum Library collections are encyclopedic in scope and parallel the strength of the museum's collections. In addition to being a research center, the library collections are frequently exhibited at the Brooklyn Museum and elsewhere. Collection highlights include special collections of fashion sketches, documentary photographs, artists\u2019 books, trade catalogs and other rare books.\n\n====Costume and Fashion Sketch Collection====\nHighlights of the fashion sketch collection include sketches by [[Elizabeth Hawes]], [[Bonnie Cashin]], [[Walter Plunkett]] and a full visual record of every design imported or created by [[Henri Bendel]] from 1912 to 1950. The museum's website has images of such collections.<ref>{{cite web|title=Libraries and Archives: Fashion and Costume Sketch Collection, 1912-1950|url=https://www.brooklynmuseum.org/opencollection/archives/set/198/fashion_and_costume_sketch_collection_1912-1950|website=Brooklyn Museum}}</ref>\n\n=====Henri Bendel Collection=====\nIn the spring of 1942, the Brooklyn Museum Libraries sent a questionnaire to seventy-five designers requesting biographical information along with sketches of their work. The questionnaire was announced in [[Women's Wear Daily]].  [[Henri Bendel]] sent a large collection of sketches rendered by design artists employed by the retailer. The artists attended Parisian shows to record the work of more than 170 designers including [[Balenciaga]], [[Chanel]], [[Dior]], [[Jeanne Lanvin|Lanvin]], [[Poiret]], [[Elsa Schiaparelli|Schiaparelli]], [[Vionnet]], and [[Charles Frederick Worth|Worth]]. In 1944, sketches from the collection were featured in an exhibition at the museum, [https://www.brooklynmuseum.org/opencollection/exhibitions/1776/French_Fashion_Sketches_from_the_Henri_Bendel_Collection French Fashion Sketches from the Henri Bendel Collection].\n\nToday, the Henri Bendel Collection represents the largest and one of the first sketch collections received, with more than 11,000 sketches of French couture imported by the company in addition to its own house designs from 1912 through 1950.<ref>{{cite book|editor=Nancy E. Friedland|title=Documenting: Costume Design|url=http://arcade.nyarc.org/search~S2?/XDocumenting%3A+Costume+Design&searchscope=2&SORT=D/XDocumenting%3A+Costume+Design&searchscope=2&SORT=D&SUBKEY=Documenting%3A+Costume+Design/1%2C5%2C5%2CB/frameset&FF=XDocumenting%3A+Costume+Design&searchscope=2&SORT=D&1%2C1%2C|accessdate=20 August 2015|date=2010|publisher=The Theatre Library Association|pages=94\u201399}}</ref>\n\n====Artists Books====\n[[Artists books]] are a special feature of the library collection with a focus on Brooklyn-based artists; artists who are exhibited by the museum or who have work in the museum\u2019s object collection; artists who create work that relates to the objects or cultures that are represented in the museum\u2019s object collections; artists who are considered to be innovators or masters in the artists books world. Recent donations include artists books from the library of [http://arcade.nyarc.org/search~S4/?searchtype=X&searcharg=From+the+Library+of+Arnold+Smoller.&searchscope=4&sortdropdown=-&SORT=DZ&extended=0&SUBMIT=Search&searchlimits=&searchorigarg=Xsmoller%26SORT%3DDZ Arnold Smoller] and the library of [http://arcade.nyarc.org/search~S2/?searchtype=X&searcharg=From+the+Library+of+Thea+Westreich%2FEthan+Wagner.westreich&searchscope=2&sortdropdown=-&SORT=DZ&extended=0&SUBMIT=Search&searchlimits=&searchorigarg=Xwestreich%26SORT%3DDZ Thea Westreich and Ethan Wagner].\n\nThe exhibition entitled ''Artist Books'', held in 2000, featured 50 books ranging from multiples to limited edition to unique works from the library collection. From 2003 to 2006, the museum featured key works from the Wilbour Library of Egyptology in a two part exhibition entitled ''Egypt Through Other Eyes: Early Travel and Exploration and the Popularization of Ancient Egypt'', that examined how Western writers and artists saw and recorded Egypt from early works on hieroglyphs to the discovery of [[Tutankhamun]]'s tomb in 1922.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Rose|first1=Mark|title=Wilbour's Legacy|journal=Archaeology|date=August 18, 2005|url=http://archive.archaeology.org/online/reviews/wilbour/index.html}}</ref>\n\n===Digital collections===\nIn an effort to provide greater access to the collections, the Brooklyn Museum Libraries have been digitizing parts of its collections. Some digital projects include the Gilded Age Project, the Bendel Fashion sketches, and Brooklyn Visual Heritage. A multi-year collaboration with [[Pratt Institute]]'s School of Information and Library Science is underway to provide a training ground for librarians and archivists and to make the library and archive collections more accessible via digital means.\n\n==New York Art Resources Consortium==\n{{Main|New York Art Resources Consortium}}\nIn 2006, The Libraries of the Brooklyn Museum, The Frick, and The Museum of Modern Art joined forces to form the [[New York Art Resources Consortium]] (NYARC). In addition to other projects, they have collaborated to build an integrated library system, known as Arcade.,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Pogrebin|first1=Robin|title=Groundbreaking Partnership Unites Decades of Research|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/03/18/arts/artsspecial/18LIBRARY.html|publisher=New York Times|date=March 14, 2010}}</ref> to provide better access to their respective collections.\n\n==Visiting==\nDuring the renovation on the 2nd floor of the Brooklyn Museum, the libraries are open with limited access to researchers. The libraries and archives are scheduled to reopen to the public in the fall of 2016. When the floor is reopened it will feature a new Gallery of Libraries and Archives as well as newly reinstalled Asian and Islamic art galleries.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{commons category-inline|Photographs from the Goodyear Archival Collection}}\n*{{official website|http://www.brooklynmuseum.org/opencollection/archives}}\n*[http://www.brooklynmuseum.org Brooklyn Museum]\n*[http://arcade.nyarc.org/search~S2 Brookmuse: the catalog of the Brooklyn Museum Libraries and Archives]\n*[http://www.brooklynvisualheritage.org Brooklyn Visual Heritage]\n*[http://gildedage.omeka.net Documenting the Gilded Age]\n*[http://nyarc.org New York Arts Resource Consortium]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Research libraries]]\n[[Category:Archives in the United States]]\n[[Category:Brooklyn Museum]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Museum\n|name = Brooklyn Museum Libraries and Archives\n|library_logo =\n|image=File:G1015 Sa5 Sanson Atlas table of contents detail.jpeg\n|caption=Nicolas Sanson. Atlas nouveau, 1692. Table of contents, detail.\n|map_type=New York City\n|map_caption = Location within New York City\n|coordinates = {{coord|40.6712062|-73.9636306|display=inline}}\n|established= {{Start date|1823}}\n|location= 200 Eastern Parkway, [[Brooklyn]], New York, NY\n|type= [[Library]]\n|collection_size= 300,000 volumes and 3,000+ linear feet archives\n|annual_circulation=\n|pop_served= \n|budget=\n|director= Deirdre Lawrence (Principal Librarian)\n|num_employees=\n|website={{url|http://www.brooklynmuseum.org/opencollection/archives/}}\n}}\nThe '''Brooklyn Museum Libraries and Archives''' holds approximately 300,000 volumes<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Lawrence|first1=Deirdre E. |title=Beyond the Galleries: The Brooklyn Museum Library Shares Its Treasures|journal=Fine Art Connoisseur|date=2008|url=http://nyarc.org/arcade/brooklyn/articles/FA_BehindScenes.pdf}}</ref> and over 3,000 linear feet of archives related to the history of the museum and its collections. The library collections comprise books, periodicals, auction catalogs, artist and institutional files as well as special collections containing photographs, sketches, artists' books, rare books and trade catalogues. The museum archives contains institutional records, curatorial correspondence, expedition reports, and other related textual and visual records dating to the founding of the institution.\n{{TOC limit|2}}\n\n==History==\nThe [[Brooklyn Museum]] evolved from the Brooklyn Apprentices' Library Association, founded in 1823, and the first free and circulating library in Brooklyn. In 1831, the library acquired its first painting, joining a developing book collection. According to the Minutes of the Apprentices' Library from January 31, 1835: \"[[Walter Whitman]] acting librarian presented a Report this evening, in which it is stated that there are now about 1200 volumes in the library in a proper \nstate for being drawn out; and that the number of Readers is 172.\"<ref>{{cite journal|title=Minutes of the Brooklyn Apprentices' Library Association, 1:84.|journal=Brooklyn Museum Archives}}</ref>\n\nBy the 1840s, the public demand for educational programs resulted in the reorganization of the library with the adoption by the association of a revised charter under the name of the Brooklyn Institute and the library was housed in a new building.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Lawrence|first1=Deirdre|title=The Evolution of a Library: The Brooklyn Museum of Art Libraries and Archives|journal=Art Documentation|date=1999|volume=18|issue=1|pages=10\u201313}}</ref> Evening classes were offered, the first exhibition of paintings was held and library acquisition funds became available. The library accession records document early institutional interest in the world at large. An early acquisition is currently in the museum's long term installation, ''Connecting Cultures''.\n\nOver the next forty years, the Brooklyn Institute grew and was reorganized into the Brooklyn Institute of Arts & Sciences, which eventually became the parent organization of the [[Brooklyn Museum]], [[Brooklyn Children's Museum]], the [[Brooklyn Academy of Music]] (BAM) and the [[Brooklyn Botanic Garden]]. During the late 1880s, plans were established to revitalize the institute in order \u2033to make the property of the Institute the nucleus of a broad and comprehensive institution for the advancement of science and art...\u2033<ref>{{cite book|title=Brooklyn Institute of Arts and Sciences. Third Yearbook of the Brooklyn Institute|date=1891|publisher=Brooklyn: Press of Eagle Book}}</ref> After an architectural competition held in 1893, the firm of [[McKim, Mead & White]] was chosen to design a building to house the Brooklyn Museum and its library.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Lawrence|first1=Deirdre|title=The Evolution of a Library: The Brooklyn Museum of Art Libraries and Archives|journal=Art Documentation|date=1999|volume=18|issue=1|pages=10\u201313}}</ref>\n\nThe early 1900s saw reorganization of the original Apprentices' Library by the museum librarians who kept portions of the collection that supported research on the museum's object collections and transferred the rest to other libraries in Brooklyn and other institutions.\n\n[[William Henry Goodyear]], the museum's first Curator of Fine Arts (1890-1923), founding museum librarian Susan A. Hutchinson (1900\u201335) and [[Stewart Culin]], the museum's first Curator of Ethnology (1903\u201329), laid the foundation of the research and object collections. Some of the rarest material in the library collection today, such as a set of documentary photographs of Mexico and Central America taken by [[Alfred P. Maudslay]] in the 1880s, was acquired under their direction. After Stewart Culin died, the trustees acquired his archives and personal library of nearly 7,000 titles, focused primarily on the arts and culture of the Americas, Asia, Africa, and Eastern Europe.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Lawrence|first1=Deirdre|title=The Evolution of a Library: The Brooklyn Museum of Art Libraries and Archives|journal=Art Documentation|date=1999|volume=18|issue=1|pages=10\u201313}}</ref>\n\n==The Libraries==\n\nToday the Brooklyn Museum has two research libraries\u2014the Art Reference Library and the Wilbour Library of Egyptology\u2014in addition to the museum archives which support research on the museum, its history and collections as well as the broader areas of art and cultural history.\n\n===Wilbour Library of Egyptology===\nThe Wilbour Library is named after [[Charles Edwin Wilbour]], 1833\u201396, one of America's first Egyptologists. During his travels to Egypt, Wilbour visited temples and tombs and copied inscriptions found on monuments in the field. He built an important resource on Ancient Egypt by collecting books from fellow Egyptologists abroad, as well as from dealers and scholarly publishers, developing his personal library as a resource to educate himself. Wilbour's personal library was enriched with scholarly annotations containing corrections and additions to the published text which are of value today as they offer unique information. In 1916, Wilbour's children offered his antiquities and library collection to the Brooklyn Museum as a memorial to their father.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Compiled by|last2=Cook, Jr.|first2=William Burt|title=Catalogue of the Egyptological and Other Books From the Collection of the Late Edwin Wilbour|date=1924|publisher=Brooklyn Museum|location=Brooklyn, New York}}</ref> After this initial donation, Wilbour's heirs continued to donate objects to the museum. In 1932, the Charles Edwin Wilbour Fund was set up by Victor Wilbour to support both the library and the Egyptian collection at the museum.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Rose|first1=Mark|title=Wilbour's Legacy|journal=Archaeology|date=August 18, 2005|url=http://archive.archaeology.org/online/reviews/wilbour/index.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Fazzini|first1=Richard A.|last2=Romano|first2=James F.|last3=Cody|first3=Madeleine E.|title=Art for eternity : masterworks from ancient Egypt|date=1999|publisher=Brooklyn Museum of Art, in association with Scala Publishers|location=Brooklyn, NY}}</ref>\n\n===Museum Archives===\nIn 1985, the Brooklyn Museum established the archives as part of the library. Textual and visual materials are available to support users in understanding the museum's object collections as well as its history and programs. Exchanges between curators and artists, collectors and donors, as well as exhibition files containing information on specific artists or works of art that have been exhibited at the museum, and object documentation tracing how an object was acquired, and more can all be found in the archives.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Lawrence|first1=Deirdre|title=The Evolution of a Library: The Brooklyn Museum of Art Libraries and Archives|journal=Art Documentation|date=1999|volume=18|issue=1|pages=10\u201313}}</ref>\n\n===Collection highlights===\nToday the Brooklyn Museum Library collections are encyclopedic in scope and parallel the strength of the museum's collections. In addition to being a research center, the library collections are frequently exhibited at the Brooklyn Museum and elsewhere. Collection highlights include special collections of fashion sketches, documentary photographs, artists\u2019 books, trade catalogs and other rare books.\n\n====Costume and Fashion Sketch Collection====\nHighlights of the fashion sketch collection include sketches by [[Elizabeth Hawes]], [[Bonnie Cashin]], [[Walter Plunkett]] and a full visual record of every design imported or created by [[Henri Bendel]] from 1912 to 1950. The museum's website has images of such collections.<ref>{{cite web|title=Libraries and Archives: Fashion and Costume Sketch Collection, 1912-1950|url=https://www.brooklynmuseum.org/opencollection/archives/set/198/fashion_and_costume_sketch_collection_1912-1950|website=Brooklyn Museum}}</ref>\n\n=====Henri Bendel Collection=====\nIn the spring of 1942, the Brooklyn Museum Libraries sent a questionnaire to seventy-five designers requesting biographical information along with sketches of their work. The questionnaire was announced in [[Women's Wear Daily]].  [[Henri Bendel]] sent a large collection of sketches rendered by design artists employed by the retailer. The artists attended Parisian shows to record the work of more than 170 designers including [[Balenciaga]], [[Chanel]], [[Dior]], [[Jeanne Lanvin|Lanvin]], [[Poiret]], [[Elsa Schiaparelli|Schiaparelli]], [[Vionnet]], and [[Charles Frederick Worth|Worth]]. In 1944, sketches from the collection were featured in an exhibition at the museum, [https://www.brooklynmuseum.org/opencollection/exhibitions/1776/French_Fashion_Sketches_from_the_Henri_Bendel_Collection French Fashion Sketches from the Henri Bendel Collection].\n\nToday, the Henri Bendel Collection represents the largest and one of the first sketch collections received, with more than 11,000 sketches of French couture imported by the company in addition to its own house designs from 1912 through 1950.<ref>{{cite book|editor=Nancy E. Friedland|title=Documenting: Costume Design|url=http://arcade.nyarc.org/search~S2?/XDocumenting%3A+Costume+Design&searchscope=2&SORT=D/XDocumenting%3A+Costume+Design&searchscope=2&SORT=D&SUBKEY=Documenting%3A+Costume+Design/1%2C5%2C5%2CB/frameset&FF=XDocumenting%3A+Costume+Design&searchscope=2&SORT=D&1%2C1%2C|accessdate=20 August 2015|date=2010|publisher=The Theatre Library Association|pages=94\u201399}}</ref>\n\n====Artists Books====\n[[Artists books]] are a special feature of the library collection with a focus on Brooklyn-based artists; artists who are exhibited by the museum or who have work in the museum\u2019s object collection; artists who create work that relates to the objects or cultures that are represented in the museum\u2019s object collections; artists who are considered to be innovators or masters in the artists books world. Recent donations include artists books from the library of [http://arcade.nyarc.org/search~S4/?searchtype=X&searcharg=From+the+Library+of+Arnold+Smoller.&searchscope=4&sortdropdown=-&SORT=DZ&extended=0&SUBMIT=Search&searchlimits=&searchorigarg=Xsmoller%26SORT%3DDZ Arnold Smoller] and the library of [http://arcade.nyarc.org/search~S2/?searchtype=X&searcharg=From+the+Library+of+Thea+Westreich%2FEthan+Wagner.westreich&searchscope=2&sortdropdown=-&SORT=DZ&extended=0&SUBMIT=Search&searchlimits=&searchorigarg=Xwestreich%26SORT%3DDZ Thea Westreich and Ethan Wagner].\n\nThe exhibition entitled ''Artist Books'', held in 2000, featured 50 books ranging from multiples to limited edition to unique works from the library collection. From 2003 to 2006, the museum featured key works from the Wilbour Library of Egyptology in a two part exhibition entitled ''Egypt Through Other Eyes: Early Travel and Exploration and the Popularization of Ancient Egypt'', that examined how Western writers and artists saw and recorded Egypt from early works on hieroglyphs to the discovery of [[Tutankhamun]]'s tomb in 1922.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Rose|first1=Mark|title=Wilbour's Legacy|journal=Archaeology|date=August 18, 2005|url=http://archive.archaeology.org/online/reviews/wilbour/index.html}}</ref>\n\n===Digital collections===\nIn an effort to provide greater access to the collections, the Brooklyn Museum Libraries have been digitizing parts of its collections. Some digital projects include the Gilded Age Project, the Bendel Fashion sketches, and Brooklyn Visual Heritage. A multi-year collaboration with [[Pratt Institute]]'s School of Information and Library Science is underway to provide a training ground for librarians and archivists and to make the library and archive collections more accessible via digital means.\n\n==New York Art Resources Consortium==\n{{Main article|New York Art Resources Consortium}}\nIn 2006, The Libraries of the Brooklyn Museum, The Frick, and The Museum of Modern Art joined forces to form the [[New York Art Resources Consortium]] (NYARC). In addition to other projects, they have collaborated to build an integrated library system, known as Arcade.,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Pogrebin|first1=Robin|title=Groundbreaking Partnership Unites Decades of Research|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/03/18/arts/artsspecial/18LIBRARY.html|publisher=New York Times|date=March 14, 2010}}</ref> to provide better access to their respective collections.\n\n==Visiting==\nDuring the renovation on the 2nd floor of the Brooklyn Museum, the libraries are open with limited access to researchers. The libraries and archives are scheduled to reopen to the public in the fall of 2016. When the floor is reopened it will feature a new Gallery of Libraries and Archives as well as newly reinstalled Asian and Islamic art galleries.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{commons category-inline|Photographs from the Goodyear Archival Collection}}\n*{{official website|http://www.brooklynmuseum.org/opencollection/archives}}\n*[http://www.brooklynmuseum.org Brooklyn Museum]\n*[http://arcade.nyarc.org/search~S2 Brookmuse: the catalog of the Brooklyn Museum Libraries and Archives]\n*[http://www.brooklynvisualheritage.org Brooklyn Visual Heritage]\n*[http://gildedage.omeka.net Documenting the Gilded Age]\n*[http://nyarc.org New York Arts Resource Consortium]\n\n[[Category:Research libraries]]\n[[Category:Archives in the United States]]\n[[Category:Brooklyn Museum]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brooklyn_Museum_Libraries_and_Archives"}
{"title_page": "Cis (mathematics)", "text_new": "{{lowercase title}}\n{{short description|mathematical notation}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019|cs1-dates=y}}\n{{math|'''cis'''}}<!-- with a lower-case \"c\" --> is a less commonly used [[mathematical notation]] defined by {{math|cis(''x'') {{=}} cos(''x'') + ''i'' sin(''x'')}},<ref name=\"Weisstein_cis\"/><ref name=\"Byrnes_2004\"/><ref name=\"Swokowski_2011\"/><ref name=\"Simmons_2014_1\"/><ref name=\"Simmons_2014_2\"/><ref name=\"Kammler_2008\"/><ref name=\"Lorenzo-Hartley_2016\"/><ref name=\"Pierce_2016\"/><ref name=\"Beebe_2017\"/> where {{math|cos}} is the [[cosine]] function, {{math|''i''}} is the [[imaginary unit]] and {{math|sin}} is the [[sine]] function. The notation is less commonly used than [[Euler's formula]], <math>e^{ix}</math>, which offers an even shorter and more general notation for {{math|cos(''x'') + ''i'' sin(''x'')}}.\n\n==Overview==\nThe {{math|cis}} notation was first coined by [[William Rowan Hamilton]] in ''Elements of Quaternions'' (1866)<ref name=\"Hamilton_1866\"/><ref name=\"Hamilton_1899\"/> and subsequently used by [[Irving Stringham]] in works such as ''Uniplanar Algebra'' (1893),<ref name=\"Stringham_1893\"/><ref name=\"Cajori_1929\"/> or by [[James Harkness]] and [[Frank Morley]] in their ''Introduction to the Theory of Analytic Functions'' (1898).<ref name=\"Cajori_1929\"/><ref name=\"Harkness_Morley_1898\"/> It connects [[trigonometric function]]s with [[exponential function]]s in the [[complex plane]] via [[Euler's formula]].\n\nIt is mostly used as a convenient shorthand notation to simplify some expressions,<ref name=\"Swokowski_2011\"/><ref name=\"Hamilton_1866\"/><ref name=\"Stringham_1893\"/><ref name=\"Reis_2011\"/><ref name=\"Weitz_2016\"/> for example in conjunction with [[Fourier transform|Fourier]] and [[Hartley transform]]s,<ref name=\"Byrnes_2004\"/><ref name=\"Kammler_2008\"/><ref name=\"Lorenzo-Hartley_2016\"/> or when exponential functions shouldn't be used for some reason in math education.\n\nIn information technology, the function sees dedicated support in various high-performance math libraries (such as [[Intel]]'s [[Math Kernel Library]]<ref name=\"Intel_MKL\"/>), available for many compilers, programming languages (including [[C (programming language)|C]], [[C++]],<ref name=\"Intel_2007_C++\"/> [[Common Lisp]],<ref name=\"Lisp\"/><ref name=\"Lisp_2005\"/> [[D (programming language)|D]],<ref name=\"D_2011\"/> [[Fortran]],<ref name=\"Intel_2008_Fortran\"/> [[Haskell (programming language)|Haskell]],<ref name=\"Haskell\"/> [[Julia (programming language)|Julia]]<ref name=\"Julia\"/>), and operating systems (including [[Windows]], [[Linux]],<ref name=\"Intel_2008_Fortran\"/> [[macOS]] and [[HP-UX]]<ref name=\"HP_2007_UX\"/>). Depending on the platform the fused operation is about twice as fast as calling the sine and cosine functions individually.<ref name=\"D_2011\"/><ref name=\"Rationale_2003_C\"/>\n\n==Relation to the complex exponential function==\nThe [[complex exponential function]] can be expressed\n\n:<math>e^{ix} = \\cos(x) + i\\sin(x),</math><ref name=\"Weisstein_cis\"/>\n\n:<math>e^{-ix} = \\cos(-x) + i\\sin(-x) = \\cos(x) - i\\sin(x)</math>\n\n:<math>e^{i\\pi} = -1</math>\n\n:<math>\\cos(x) = \\frac{e^{ix} + e^{-ix}}{2} </math>\n\n:<math>\\sin(x) = \\frac{e^{ix} - e^{-ix}}{2i} </math>\n\nwhere {{math|''i''<sup>2</sup> {{=}} \u22121}}.\n\nThis can also be expressed using the following notation\n\n:<math>\\operatorname{cis}(x) = \\cos(x) + i\\sin(x),</math><ref name=\"Weisstein_cis\"/><ref name=\"Simmons_2014_1\"/><ref name=\"Rationale_2003_C\"/>\n\ni.e. \"{{math|cis}}\" abbreviates \"{{math|cos + ''i'' sin}}\".\n\nThough at first glance this notation is redundant, being equivalent to {{math|''e<sup>ix</sup>''}}, its use is rooted in several advantages, such as being directly tied to the polar form of a complex number (and being easier to grasp).\n\n== Mathematical identities ==\n\n===Derivative===\n\n:<math>\\frac{\\mathrm{d}}{\\mathrm{d}z}\\operatorname{cis}(z) = i\\operatorname{cis}(z) = ie^{iz}</math><ref name=\"Weisstein_cis\"/><ref name=\"Fuchs_2011_2\"/>\n\n=== Integral ===\n:<math>\\int\\operatorname{cis}(z)\\,\\mathrm{d}z = -i\\operatorname{cis}(z) = -ie^{iz}</math><ref name=\"Weisstein_cis\"/>\n\n=== Other properties ===\nThese follow directly from [[Euler's formula]].\n\n:<math>\\operatorname{cis}(x+y) = \\operatorname{cis}(x)\\,\\operatorname{cis}(y)</math><ref name=\"Fuchs_2011_1\"/>\n\n:<math>\\operatorname{cis}(x-y) = {\\operatorname{cis}(x) \\over \\operatorname{cis}(y)}</math>\n\nThe identities above hold if {{math|''x''}} and {{math|''y''}} are any complex numbers. If {{math|''x''}} and {{math|''y''}} are real, then\n:<math>|\\operatorname{cis}(x) - \\operatorname{cis}(y)| \\le |x-y|.</math><ref name=\"Fuchs_2011_1\"/>\n\n== History ==\n{{Refimprove section|date=November 2017}}\n\nThis notation was more common in the post\u2013World War II era, when typewriters were used to convey mathematical expressions.\n\nSuperscripts are both offset vertically and smaller than '{{math|cis}}' or '{{math|exp}}'; hence, they can be problematic even for hand-writing, for example, {{math|''e''<sup>''ix''<sup>2</sup></sup>}} versus {{math|cis(''x''<sup>2</sup>)}} or {{math|exp(''ix''<sup>2</sup>)}}. For many readers, {{math|cis(''x''<sup>2</sup>)}} is the clearest, easiest to read of the three.{{citation needed|date=June 2016}}\n\nThe {{math|cis}} notation is sometimes used to emphasize one method of viewing and dealing with a problem over another. The mathematics of trigonometry and exponentials are related but not exactly the same; exponential notation emphasizes the whole, whereas {{math|cis(''x'')}} and {{math|cos(''x'') + ''i'' sin(''x'')}} notations emphasize the parts. This can be rhetorically useful to mathematicians and engineers when discussing this function, and further serve as a [[mnemonic]] (for {{math|cos + ''i'' sin}}).\n\nThe {{math|cis}} notation is convenient for math students whose knowledge of trigonometry and complex numbers permit this notation, but whose conceptual understanding does not yet permit the notation {{math|''e<sup>ix</sup>''}}.  As students learn concepts that build on prior knowledge, it is important not to force them into levels of math for which they are not yet prepared: the usual proof that {{math|cis(''x'') {{=}} ''e<sup>ix</sup>''}} requires [[calculus]], which the student may not have studied before encountering the expression {{math|cos(''x'') + ''i'' sin(''x'')}}.\n\nIn 1942, inspired by the {{math|cis}} notation, [[Ralph V. L. Hartley]] introduced the {{math|[[cas (mathematics)|cas]]}} (for ''cosine-and-sine'') function for the real-valued [[Hartley kernel]], a meanwhile established shortcut in conjunction with [[Hartley transform]]s:<ref name=\"Hartley_1942\"/><ref name=\"Bracewell_1999\"/>\n\n{{math|cas(''x'') {{=}} cos(''x'') + sin(''x'')}}.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[De Moivre's formula]]\n* [[Euler's formula]]\n* [[Complex number]]\n* [[Ptolemy's theorem]]\n* [[Phasor]]\n* [[Versor]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"Byrnes_2004\">{{cite book |title=Computational Noncommutative Algebra and Applications |editor-first=Jim |editor-last=Byrnes |chapter=Fast Color Wavelet-Haar-Hartley-Prometheus Transforms for Image Processing |pages=401\u2013411 |first1=Ekaterina |last1=L.-Rundblad |first2=Alexei |last2=Maidan |first3=Peter |last3=Novak |first4=Valeriy |last4=Labunets |doi=10.1007/1-4020-2307-3 |publisher=[[Springer Science + Business Media]] |location=Dordrecht, Netherlands |date=2004 |isbn=978-1-4020-1982-1}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Simmons_2014_1\">{{cite web |title=Cis |author-first=Bruce |author-last=Simmons |date=2014-07-28 |orig-year=2004 |work=Mathwords: Terms and Formulas from Algebra I to Calculus |publisher=[[Clackamas Community College]], Mathematics Department |location=Oregon City, OR, US |url=http://www.mathwords.com/c/cis.htm |access-date=2016-01-15}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Simmons_2014_2\">{{cite web |title=Polar Form of a Complex Number |author-first=Bruce |author-last=Simmons |date=2014-07-28 |orig-year=2004 |work=Mathwords: Terms and Formulas from Algebra I to Calculus |publisher=[[Clackamas Community College]], Mathematics Department |location=Oregon City, OR, US |url=http://www.mathwords.com/p/polar_form_of_a_complex_number.htm |access-date=2016-01-15}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Kammler_2008\">{{cite book |title=A First Course in Fourier Analysis |author-first=David W. |author-last=Kammler |publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]] |date=2008-01-17 |edition=2 |isbn=978-1-13946903-6 |id={{ISBN|1-13946903-7}} |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=znP-ADtE8ZQC |access-date=2017-10-28}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Lorenzo-Hartley_2016\">{{cite book |title=The Fractional Trigonometry: With Applications to Fractional Differential Equations and Science |author-first1=Carl F. |author-last1=Lorenzo |author-first2=Tom T. |author-last2=Hartley |publisher=[[John Wiley & Sons]] |date=2016-11-14 |isbn=978-1-11913942-3 |id={{ISBN|1-11913942-2}} |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LdyADQAAQBAJ |access-date=2017-10-28}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Pierce_2016\">{{cite web |author-first=Rod |author-last=Pierce |title=Complex Number Multiplication |work=Maths Is Fun |date=2016-01-04 |orig-year=2000 |url=http://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/complex-number-multiply.html |access-date=2016-01-15}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Hamilton_1866\">{{cite book |title=Elements of Quaternions |author-first=William Rowan |author-last=Hamilton |author-link=William Rowan Hamilton |date=1866-01-01 |edition=1 |editor-first=William Edwin |editor-last=Hamilton |editor-link=William Edwin Hamilton |publisher=[[Longmans, Green & Co.]] |publication-place=London |chapter=Chapter II. Fractional powers, General roots of unity |pages=250\u2013257, 260, 262\u2013263 |url=https://archive.org/stream/bub_gb_fIRAAAAAIAAJ#page/n5/mode/1up |access-date=2016-01-17 |quote=[\u2026] {{nobr|cos [\u2026] + ''i'' sin [\u2026]}} we shall occasionally ''abridge'' to the following: [\u2026] cis [\u2026]. As to the marks [\u2026], they are to be considered as chiefly available for the present ''exposition'' of the system, and as not often wanted, nor employed, in the subsequent ''practise'' thereof; and the same remark applies to the recent ''abrigdement'' cis, for {{nobr|cos + ''i'' sin}} [\u2026]}} ([https://archive.org/stream/elementsquaterni00hamirich#page/n0/mode/1up], [https://archive.org/details/elementsquatern02hamigoog]) (NB. This work was published posthumously, Hamilton died in 1865.)</ref>\n<ref name=\"Hamilton_1899\">{{cite book |title=Elements of Quaternions |first=William Rowan |last=Hamilton |author-link=William Rowan Hamilton |editor-first1=William Edwin |editor-last1=Hamilton |editor-link1=William Edwin Hamilton |editor-first2=Charles Jasper |editor-last2=Joly |editor-link2=Charles Jasper Joly |date=1899 |edition=2nd |volume=I |publisher=[[Longmans, Green & Co.]] |location=London |page=262 |url=https://archive.org/details/117770258_001 |access-date=2019-08-03 |quote=[\u2026] recent ''abridgment'' cis for {{nobr|cos + ''i'' sin}} [\u2026]}} (NB. This edition was reprinted by {{ill|Chelsea Publishing Company{{!}}Chelsea Publ. Co.|de|Chelsea Publishing Company}} in 1969.)</ref>\n<ref name=\"Stringham_1893\">{{anchor|Stringham-1893}}{{cite book |title=Uniplanar Algebra, being part&nbsp;1 of a prop\u00e6deutic to the higher mathematical analysis |author-first=Irving |author-last=Stringham |author-link=Irving Stringham |date=1893-07-01 |orig-year=1891 |edition=1 |volume=1 |publisher=[[The Berkeley Press]] |others=C. A. Mordock & Co. (printer) |location=San Francisco, US |pages=71\u201375, 77, 79\u201380, 82, 84\u201386, 89, 91\u201392, 94\u201395, 100\u2013102, 116, 123, 128\u2013129, 134\u2013135 |url=https://archive.org/details/uniplanaralgebra00stri |access-date=2016-01-18 |quote=As an abbreviation for {{nobr|cos ''\u03b8'' + ''i'' sin ''\u03b8''}} it is convenient t